ref_text: Sun don't shine in the shade, ugh
tate_text:
All Kanye ever wanted to do was shine, but after his mother’s passing, the very public breakdown of his relationship with Alexis Phifer, and the pressures and trappings of fame, Kanye fell in to depression. He used that pain to create the influential, though often critically neglected, 808s & Heartbreak, shining a light that the entire music industry began to follow.

Interestingly, the symbol of light vs dark has been prevalent in art since the Classical period, when the protagonists of Greek Tragedy (a genre ‘Ye has referenced in the past) would appeal to the light at their lowest moment, as they enter the darkness. Christianity, a major theme on this album, also uses the symbol, as alluded to by Chance here. It is one of the governing symbols of ‘Ye’s oeuvre and perfectly sums up the human narrative: good and bad; light and dark.

In the end they catch him and Em yells out “kids!”, then shows the explicit content label, implying kids shouldn’t listen to him. But this was all done tongue in cheek, it was more of a parody of how parents think people should go through great efforts to keep their kids away from Eminem.

tate_text:
A picture is said to be worth a thousand words. The speaker wishes he could open up to this girl and tell his story in a way that an illustration would, but pain from his past makes him fearful of showing his vulnerable side.

Cole details this debilitating psyche on the album’s previous track, “Ville Mentality.” He similarly voices his frustration on 2014 Forest Hill Drive’s “January 28th.”

tate_text: After the outro, the track continues in silence for about 40 seconds. The moment of silence is a dedication to the victims of the Manchester Bombing that occurred in Manchester, United Kingdom, following Ariana’s performance on her Dangerous Woman Tour. The extra 40 seconds makes the song’s duration 5:22, which commemorates the day the bombing occurred on May 22nd, or 5/22.

These lines relate to masochism, the feeling of pleasure after receiving pain. For some, masochism can be a debilitating psychosexual disorder.

X has a track called “Pain = BESTFRIEND,” which was made back in March 2018 for his album ?, the song may be hinting at possible masochistic feelings.

X also mentioned masochism on his April 2016 track, “I spoke to the devil in miami, he said everything would be fine”:

Word of a pacifist to war of a masochist

ref_text: Oblivion hole cold, oblivious
tate_text:
Nice play on words here by X – He uses “Oblivion hole cold” to explain the concept of death:


When you’re dead you’re unconscious to the world around you (oblivion)
You’re most likely in a hole due to being buried in a coffin
Coldness is synonymous with death, with both your lifeless body and the ground around you (which is colder because of the six feet of depth you’re buried at) being cold.



X then follows up with oblivious to continue on from his previous lines, implying the murderers of these innocent people are unaware of the damage they cause in the long run to their victim, the victims family, friends and the local community – they’re ignorant

ref_text:
My nigga, I ain't ever letting you go again
 I ain't ever letting go
 I ain't ever letting you go again
 Please give me my soul
 I ain't ever letting go
 I ain't ever letting you go again
 Please give me my soul
 I ain't ever letting go
 But the Devil don't play fair
tate_text:
This is a conversation between J. Cole and the Devil.

The previous set of lines explains how preachers would say Cole needs Jesus, but since he wants to be famous, he has to sell his soul to the Devil in order to succeed. Now, he’s asking for his soul back, but the Devil is not budging, telling him that he’s never letting go of him again. Hence Cole is heard saying “The Devil don’t play fair”.

Cole is suggesting here (as he was in the whole album) that he’s back from making “radio music”,  and he’s gonna keep making “real music”. It also fits in with the upcoming lines about re-adjusted his target audience and re-introducing himself, as well as the track “Let Nas Down”, where Cole is expressing that, when he couldn’t get a radio hit by sticking true to his lyrics with singles like “Who Dat”, he dumbed himself down and “sold his soul” with mainstream songs like “Work Out”.

Although “Work Out” was a success as a single, alot of Cole’s fans were let down because he strayed so far from the original Cole on The Come Up and The Warm Up. When he is saying that he wants his soul back, it can mean that he wants his real fans back, rather than his “radio fans”, and once he gets us back, he’ll never let us go again.

Psst, if you listen close enough you’ll hear Lil' Cole in the background.

 I helped you out of a broken place
 You gave me comfort

tate_text:
Abel is likely referring to his ex-girlfriend, Selena Gomez, whom he dated for 10 months. During this period, he helped her through her battle with Lupus, even canceling a few shows on his “Legend of the Fall” tour to be by her side.

According to an insider:

Abel has been one of her biggest supports. She had been traveling with him on his tour and he was off during her surgery and right after during her recovery.

Gomez also consistently appeared on Abel’s social handles. For example, during their vacation to Italy at the end of January, she appeared on his Instagram story.

ref_text: No, I’m not alone
tate_text:
He’s really saying that he’s not the only one experiencing this kind of feeling. How does he “have her” when he’s talking about trying to find “her?”

Playing into the next line, “ Even though nothing was the same” could also be Drake answering a girlfriend’s/lover’s question about cheating (“Are you alone right now? Who are you with?”); Drake answers honestly (“I’m not alone” = I’m with a girl), but “nothing was the same” means that sex with the other girl wasn’t as good or meaningful as sex with his lover / steady girl. He’s being honest and self-loathing.

ref_text: When you're grinding up your teeth and it's fucking hard to sleep
tate_text:
MDMA makes the jaws clench, which is why Abel was chewing gum earlier. The discomfort and lack of motor control makes sleeping difficult.

The line could also be heard as:

When you’re grinding up your teeth and it’s fucking hard to see

If enough MDMA is taken, vision can become blurred as well. The user’s eyes become twitchy and roll out of focus, and the brain loses its ability to process visual information.

Either way, Abel already knows what this girl may potentially suffer through, but he doesn’t care since it was her decision to get involved in the lifestyle.

ref_text:
I'm sorry, Mama, I never meant to hurt you
 I never meant to make you cry
 But tonight I'm cleanin' out my closet (One more time!)
 I said I'm sorry, Mama, I never meant to hurt you
 I never meant to make you cry
 But tonight I'm cleanin' out my closet (Ha!)
tate_text:
Eminem is airing all his feelings out. The metaphor "cleaning out my closet" refers to him not holding his tongue anymore, And it’s a double meaning, he’s finally going to leave his mom in peace, Because he is finished with her abusive nature and also letting go of his feelings.

Of course, those sentences all have an ironic meaning. With this song he wants to hurt his mum and wants to make her cry because all the things she did to him. As he raps about later in the song:

Witnessin' your momma poppin' prescription pills in the kitchen

This is Cole’s way of bragging about his car’s suicide doors, which are hinged at the rear instead of the front.



Cole plays off of his fancy doors by referencing a method of suicide: Slitting wrists.

He coveted a car with suicide doors back in 2010 on “I’m On It”.

After criticizing rappers who only talk about money, he commits lyrical suicide a few lines later by doing the exact same thing.

Ib gon' ask me how I did this shit
 I'm gon' do a humble stunt act like I meant this shit
 Thats the ego taking credit for what God made
 Fuck this album shit, hey mama look what God made
tate_text:
Ib – short for Ibrahim Hamad – is the president and co-founder of Cole’s record label Dreamville Records.

In reflecting on the birth of Cole’s daughter, Ib ponders how such a close friend of his is responsible for such a monumental moment. Throughout his career, Cole has expressed the weight and importance he’s put on creating great music. But now, with a new life in his arms, not even his music – not even himself – is more important than his newborn. And much like Chance the Rapper, he realizes this blessing is way beyond anything his Earthly being was capable of manifesting. Instead, this was truly the work of God.

It’s about loving yourself, being confident throughout the day and looking at life that way. There’s a lot out there to love and there’s a lot of love to give, and if you do, you’ll feel that way. You’ll feel the love.

ref_text:
Call it trap 'cause it's a total setup
 Hopin' that you rappers fall in that
tate_text:
Eminem is using “trap” as double entendre here.

As has been widely discussed, Eminem disses an abundance of trap/mumble rappers on Kamikaze, including Lil Pump, Lil Xan & Machine Gun Kelly.

In other words, Eminem is saying Kamikaze is literal “trap” music for the trap/mumble rappers.  He is hoping that they fall into the “trap” and respond to his disses because he knows their responses will look weak in comparison.

Another interpretation is that trap rappers have set themselves up for Eminem’s “trap” by writing such terrible lyrics in the first place.

MGK could’ve already fallen into Em’s trap.

ref_text: Or die from waitin' on it, die 'cause I'm movin' too fast
tate_text:
The expression “live fast, die young”—coined by Chicago writer Willard Motley in his 1947 critically-acclaimed novel Knock On Any Door—usually means to perform potentially risky actions you wouldn’t normally do in order to add excitement to your life.

This kind of thought is in the minds of many people (un)aware of their own mortality or those in a terminal situation who are essentially “waiting to die.” Kendrick talked about a situation where “The Art of Peer Pressure” caused him to move a little too fast while later thinking about the potential payback:


I never was a gangbanger, I mean
I never was stranger to the fonk neither, I really doubt it
Rush a nigga quick and then we laugh about it
That’s ironic, ‘cause I’ve never been violent
Until I’m with the homies

I’m usually a true firm believer of bad karma
Consequences from evil will make your past haunt ya

ref_text:
I wrote some raps that made sure that my lifeline reekin'
 The scent of a reaper, ensurin' that my allegiance
 With the other side may come soon, and if I'm doomed
tate_text:
https://soundcloud.com/rapgenius/kendrick-on

Reeking the scent – yeah, reeking the scent. Basically coming to grips with reality, saying I’m a teenager, I am out here, and there is possibly a chance that I won’t see tomorrow, so looking in the mirror and really understanding that was a tough point to deal with, a tough time to deal with. I could walk out there – there was one particular summer that was so hot you couldn’t even walk to the corner because the neighborhoods was feuding that crazy. If you walked to the corner for sure you were going to run into some action because somebody is on the other end of the corner, waiting for you to walk on that corner. That is how crazy Compton is, you know. You are waiting on that corner, you pull up, they hop out, shoot at you down the block so that you could run the opposite way, and have another car waiting on you as soon as you get to the corner, and that’s it for you. You ain’t got nowhere to go, you feel me? And you come to grips with that. You look in the mirror and say damn, this might be my last day walking out here as a teenager, you feel me? That is what that particular line, and that whole verse, is about really – grasping the idea of death, for a kid.

ref_text:
These rappers insecure
 They talk about being a man so much
 I finally understand that they ain't even sure
 'Bout who they are and why they do this
 Guess I'm included in that category as a nigga who done had the glory
tate_text:
J. Cole may be referring to the success of his breakthrough single “Work Out” and the backlash he faced from his role model Nas.

In May 2010, J. Cole released “Who Dat,” which was supposed to be the lead single from his debut album Cole World : The Sideline Story. The song failed to achieve success in the charts, so Cole kept working on his debut album, trying to come up with better and catchier tunes. A year later, his label Roc Nation was finally satisfied with “Work Out,” a song that took a step back from J. Cole’s usual lyricism. It became the album’s lead single and J. Cole’s biggest hit single to date, and is arguably what turned him into a mainstream act.

This song may have brought J. Cole the “glory” and recognition from a wider audience, but his idol Nas expressed dislike for the song and disappointment in Cole’s abandon of lyricism.

Cole famously talked about this issue on “Let Nas Down”, from his sophomore effort Born Sinner.

ref_text:
Suck on my balls, pause, I had enough
 I ain't thinking 'bout you
 I ain't thinking 'bout
tate_text:
Beyoncé tells the cheating man to “suck on my balls"—she’s showing him the same disrespect he’s shown her.  Of course, as a woman, telling a man to "suck my balls” is also a statement of strength and masculinity. Whatever power this man once held, Beyoncé’s now taken for herself. She pays him no mind.

These lyrics appear to mock part of Jay Z’s verse on Kanye West’s “So Appalled”:

I’m fresher than you all, so I don’t have to pause
All of y'all can suck my balls through my drawers

Saying “pause” after saying something sexually suggestive is a little meme in its own right.  The use of the term originated in Harlem as a way to dissociate oneself from something that could inadvertently sound like a piece of homosexual bawdy. It was popularized (along with the more blatantly offensive “no homo”) by Harlem rappers Dipset. The Boondocks animated series also used “pause” as a recurring gag. While the “pause-no homo” game has been widely condemned as homophobic, Bey is showing off a winking irony by using the term here. (Sorry…not sorry.)

ref_text:
It's not a place
 This country is to me a sound
 Of drum and bass
tate_text:
The U2 segment is a sample from the 2017 song “American Soul” which appeared on the album, Songs of Experience. On “American Soul,” Kendrick returns the favor with some spoken word poetry.

These lines are broadly interpretable, but the song’s content suggests “drum and bass” represent gunfire.

Author and music critic, Steven Hyden, suggests the following interpretation in a close look at the collaboration, which emphasizes the themes in common with other U2 songs:

Bono’s vocal hook is an extremely Bono vocal hook, in that it seems to communicate broad truths without quite making literal sense… . Aside from the shout-out to his boys Larry and Adam, what Bono seems to hint at is a familiar theme from many U2 songs: Mankind perpetually feels dislocated in every way — physically, emotionally, spiritually —–which inevitably sends our eyes heavenward in search of guidance and, hopefully, deliverance. Later, Lamar distills this feeling down to a question: “But is America honest or do we bask in sin?”

“Larry and Adam” refer to Larry Mullen Jr. and Adam Clayton, the percussionist and bassist of U2. Bono’s reference to “the sound of drum and bass” is probably figurative, but it is also definitely literally referencing the song’s new riff, presumably played by Larry and Adam.

The bells getting loud, ain't nowhere to hide
 Got nowhere to go, put away my pride
 Tired of feeling low even when I'm high
 Ain't no way to live, do I wanna die?
 I don't know, I don't know
 Bells getting loud, ain't nowhere to hide
 Got nowhere to go, put away my pride
 Tired of feeling low even when I'm high
 Ain't no way to live, do I wanna die?
 I don't know, I don't know
tate_text:
Church bells ring when someone dies. The bells getting louder suggests Cole believes his death is growing imminent.

Despite his successes and the typically euphoric effects of marijuana, he can’t escape his depression. He contemplates whether or not he wants to continue living, echoing the sentiment of Hamlet’s “To be, or not to be” soliloquy.

If this song is from the perspective of Cole’s late friend, as so much of this album is, then these lines would link with the album’s closing verse, specifically the moment Cole’s friend speaks with him on the phone:

I’ve been having premonitions
Just call it visions from the other side
I got a feeling I won’t see tomorrow
Like the time I’m living on is borrowed

Swear I wanna die, yeah, when you cross my—
 Said I wanna die, yuh, no, I'm not alright, yuh
tate_text:
X struggles mentally and is always tipping on the edge of suicide, hence the “swear I wanna die” line. However, he keeps a promise to his friends and fanbase that he would never take his own life, as stated here in the “said I wouldn’t die” line, even though he is constantly feeling pain.

Suicide is a common theme throughout X’s music, for example, the song “Jocelyn Flores” is dedicated to close friend of X’s who committed suicide in May 2017. X is among a new generation of people in the Hip-hop community known for bringing public attention to mental health, speaking about his own issues, and being a voice for others.

ref_text:
Crazy how life works
 You got a knot in your chest, imagine how a knife hurts
 You stabbed Un over some records
 Your excuse was "He was talkin' too reckless!"
tate_text:
On December 2, 1999, Jay made an appearance at a release party in New York City for Q-Tip’s debut album Amplified. Also in attendance was Lance “Un” Rivera, a record producer and close friend of The Notorious B.I.G.

At the time, Jay was preparing to release his fourth studio album, Vol. 3… Life and Times of S. Carter, on December 28th. Allegations that Lance Rivera helped bootleg Jay’s unreleased album a month before its release date were circulating all throughout the hip-hop world.

When Jay and his crew discovered one of the supposed bootleggers was at the same nightclub, a physical altercation ensued, which resulted in a stabbing that sent Lance Rivera to the hospital. The following day, Jay admitted to being the perpetrator and turned himself in. He was facing 15 years in prison for the alleged stabbing, but was instead given three years of probation.



These lines are very different from the way Jay has rapped about the stabbing incident in the past. For example, on “Dear Summer” Jay rapped:

I don’t talk shit, I just flip it Un ya
Sorry Lance, I’m just trying to advance my quotes
I ain’t making you the butt of my jokes

ref_text: Down for the count
tate_text:
“Down for the count” is a boxing idiom. If a boxer gets knocked out the referee counts to ten and if the boxer can’t get up in that time s/he loses the match. So Eliza has definitely been “hit by the thunderbolt” here, and she’s not getting back up.

Counting is a major motif in “Hamilton” and several songs feature a count, including the next song (“Satisfied”) where Eliza’s sister counts to three, “Ten Duel Commandments,” “Take a Break,” “Blow Us All Away,” and of course “The World Was Wide Enough.” There is even a mini-count in this song–“one week later… two weeks later…” Hamilton is constantly counting down to the end of his life. Eliza endures this with him and continues to be a faithful steward of his memory after he dies. So Eliza really is down for the count! Everyone who gets married is.

They say my system is overloaded
 (Girl, what’s wrong with you? Come back down)
 I'm too much in my head, did you notice?
 (Girl, what’s wrong with you? Come back down)
 My body's here on Earth, but I'm floating
 (Girl, what’s wrong with you? Come back down)
 Disconnected, so sometimes, I feel frozen and alone
tate_text:
Ariana explained these lyrics in a May 2018 Tweet:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1001524110487310336

She experienced anxiety after the May 2017 terrorist bombing, following her performance in Manchester, United Kingdom. “My body’s here on Earth, but I’m floating,” is a psychological disorder known as depersonalization, which is when a person’s thoughts or feelings seem unreal.

 Pistol in your hand don't make you real
tate_text:
Cole revisits a prominent theme from his 2018 album KOD. Throughout the project, he attempts to replicate the inner conscious of an addict. For instance, on “The Cut Off” he says:

Gimme drink, gimme dope
Bottom line, I can’t cope

On “Motiv8,” he repeats:

I’m crackin' a smile, I’m dyin' inside
My demons are close, I’m tryin' to hide
I’m poppin' a pill, I’m feelin' alive
I’m feelin' alive, I’m feelin' alive

Cole feels that many of the youth turn to temporary, materialistic things in an effort to feel a sense of fulfillment, which connects to the outro of the song.

Continuing with the message of the track, Cole begins his usual style of a simple storytelling, but then he switches to autotune on the chorus—which is something Cole has rarely or never used in the past. This can be interpreted as implementing a “youthful” vibe to mass with the “middle child” dilemma.

tate_text:
Kendrick has dipped into the perspective of the male in this relationship. He begins the verse as a narrator which creates a greater psychic distance as he is telling this story. With the shift into this perspective, Kendrick increases the psychic distance and changes his voice literally as he raps, as well as the voice of the character in the story he is telling. This signifies the perspective switch.

ref_text: This whole rhapsody
tate_text:
A rhapsody is a work of epic poetry. Comparing the song to poetry reinforces how lyrical it is.

The pun is “rap-city”, meaning Detroit. He felt like all of Detroit had laughed at him when he choked, and he wasn’t going to have it again.

It’s possible that Em is suggesting that all of Detroit is his lab and he draws inspiration from the whole city.

ref_text: Been devoted to fuckin' up bundles of paper
tate_text:
“Fuckin' up bundles of paper” is a metaphor for making money and it also means he’s writing lyrics or taking notes. There are sounds of him “fuckin' up paper” by balling it up at the end of the song.

In December 2015, Kendrick told the New York Times:

I’m just writing, writing, writing.

The ideas of making money, writing lyrics and taking notes are all intertwined since Kendrick’s notes are transferred to songs and his songs make him money.

ref_text:
And when my time is up
 Have I done enough?
tate_text:
Here, Eliza is driven by the motive to tell Alexander’s story, to make sure that the mark that he left in America is preserved and acknowledged, as well as to achieve various things of her own accord.

She begins to adopt her late husband’s desperation to be remembered–to leave a legacy–of making the utmost of her God-given time, and doing what she can.

This is a significant transition from her initial desire to lead a simple, happy life as a loving mother and wife who is loved back: ‘That Would Be Enough’:
“…We don’t need a legacy…”

ref_text: Could've had a son or a daughter, now what you finna do?
tate_text:
X reflects on his life, imagining himself possibly having a child. He ultimately realizes that he will now never have one as his death is now more imminent than ever before.

Three days after X’s murder, it was revealed by Cleopatra Bernard, X’s mother, that an unnamed woman was pregnant with his child. Cleo announced that the child was a boy on August 22, 2018, and she continued to give updates on the child before revealing that he would be named Gekyume on November 24, 2018. The child’s mother was ultimately revealed  to be a woman named Jenesis Sanchez only a few days before SKINS‘ release.

Twinkletoes, you're breakin' my heart
 You can't fuck with me; go play somewhere, I'm busy
tate_text:
This is another diss/jab at Mobb Deep member Prodigy. Calling him twinkle toes is a reference to Prodigy’s early dance career, which Jay earlier used in this same song as a diss by calling him a ballerina.



To dance or do ballet you typically have to be light on your feet, i.e. twinkle toes .

This also further plays up on Prodigy’s lack of height as twinkle, (Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star is a kids story and song) is often a word associated with children. Small stature like (Prodigy’s) is often associated with little children.

ref_text: And they blame it on Marilyn
tate_text:
It has been reported by the students of the Columbine Shooting that the ones who shot up the school (Eric Harris & Dylan Klebold) were fans of American rock band, Marilyn Manson (though this was later proven to be false.)

Since Rock & Roll was introduced to the world, there has always been the theory that music can persuade the type of violent behavior these students committed. The band has been known for it’s arguably reckless, eerie behavior, so it’s no surprise that the public eye held Manson responsible.

It is also possible that this lyric has a much deeper meaning, criticizing the media. When something as horrid as a school shooting occurs, people are quick to point fingers at controversial music artists such as Marilyn Manson or Eminem himself, for influencing a crime that’s completely indirect to them.

Eminem mentioned something similar to this on his song “Who Knew.”

But don’t blame me when little Eric jumps off of the terrace,
you should’ve been watching him.
Apparently, you ain’t parents

ref_text:
I feel niggas been out of pocket
 I feel niggas tappin' they pockets
 I feel like debatin' on who the greatest can stop it
tate_text:
Acting “out of pocket” is a figurative English idiom meaning to act wild and out of control. It is analogous to the expression “out of line.”

Lamar couples the figurative “pocket” with the literal “pocket” in order to say that people have been acting out of control and concerned about money (“tappin' they pockets”)—speculating that a cause is the “who is the greatest rapper” debate, suggesting it should stop.

Lamar has explictly asserted his position as the greatest. He has also expressed concerns about money and his own behavior post celebrity. In the context of To Pimp A Butterfly and DAMN., these lines may be directed both externally (toward others) and internally (toward himself).

This external-internal perspective shift is also formed by Lamar’s use of “pocket"—those acting "out of pocket” are concerned with what’s inside their pockets.

ref_text:
Feel my blood runnin', swear the sky's fallin'
 I know that all this shit's fabricated
tate_text:
Ariana experienced Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) and depersonalization after the Manchester bombing. She also suffered from anxiety for a long time before that.

She details some of the symptoms she experiences as a result of this mental issues.

Anxiety triggers a fight or flight response in her body, causing her blood pressure to spike temporarily.

The sky falling seems to detail depersonalization, a disorder described as feeling disconnected or detached from one’s body and thoughts. She feels like she’s witnessing everything in an out-of-body experience.

It also linked to the general feelings which come with anxiety – where a feeling of impending doom is a common system. She feels the sky falling due to her heightened sense of fear as a result of anxiety. She realizes however the events she fears aren’t actually occurring, but rather a fabrication by her mind in a response to fear.

This reflects Cole’s distaste and lack of concern for materialistic status as he described in a 2017 documentary:

I'm way too black to burn from sunrays
 So I just meditate at the home in Pompeii
 About how I could build a new Rome in one day
tate_text:
English playwright John Heywood used the phrase “Rome wasn’t built in a day” in 1538 to make the point that great things take time to build. The always-confident Kanye accepts this challenge, and gets to plotting out the next 503 year empire in the ruins of the past empire.



Kanye should be careful, though. While dark-skinned men and women have a natural SPF of roughly 13, as compared to 3-4 for Caucasians, this does not protect them from the sun entirely. Dark-skinned reggae icon Bob Marley died of skin cancer that was initially dismissed as a soccer injury because it wasn’t known that those of African descent could get melanoma.

ref_text:
I beat yo' ass if you walk in this house
 With tears in your eyes, runnin' from Poo Poo and Prentice
 Go back outside, I beat yo' ass, lil' nigga
tate_text:
This seems like a situation where Kendrick was picked on by some neighborhood kids. If he is walking inside the house with tears in his eyes because of them, it’s likely they were bullying him.

His mother understands that it is the nature of kids to do things like this. She sends him outside to toughen him up in a sense by dealing with the bullies “Poo Poo” and “Prentice.”

This situation creates a double feeling of FEAR. Kendrick is both afraid of the bullies and the consequences of facing his mother.

tate_text:
If Cole did go back to university, people would wonder why. The girl would say “Don’t you know this shit already?” because he already graduated (from St. John’s University, Magna Cum Laude). She would say “Nigga ain’t you rich already?” because he has already made it in the rap game. She thinks he should already know the material and should be focusing on his rap career.

He claims that hanging around with rappers has made him dumb. It’s a prejudice that most rappers are uneducated, but the fact is that Cole is one of only few rappers with a college degree. He feels like having lost the knowledge and intellect he had gained from graduating college, which is why in recent interviews you hear Cole say “I’m going back to college” with the intention to get smarter.

He certainly also understands getting smarter as an opportunity to enhance his lyrical abilities. He wants to write more songs with “smart” and “real” lyrics, instead of songs with “dumb” messages like “Work Out” only to sell records.

The girl sounds like the girl form “I’m a Fool”

She told me “Cole, I love you rode with you way before the riches
But you way too educated to be calling women bitches
And calling brothas niggas, pardon if I cross a line
But all this time knew you was different than all them other niggas”
I responded to her “please don’t put me on a pedestal
Cuz I know better and I’m still a fool”

ref_text: Energized like a nine volt
tate_text:
In this play on words, Eminem uses the word energized which bears close resemblance to Energizer, the household battery brand from America. Of course, the nine volt battery itself is a common one, and carries electricity through a circuit, making it energized.

This plays into the previous line, as a bolt of electricity is famously what brings Frankenstein’s Monster to life in notable film portrayals of the story



Furthermore, Dre is the one who “brought him to life,” after he was “energized” by the 9-song “Slim Shady EP” which brought him to Dre’s attention.

tate_text:
Thick skin : The ability to withstand criticism and show no signs of any criticism you may receive getting to you..

His self esteem is so high (shooting through the roof) that its gotten his skin thickness to be bullet proof. He is in other words, way too confident for shabby criticism to even touch him. Notice the gun theme with the play on “shooting through the roof” and “bullet proof”. Could also link to the previous tool theme as a firearm is in slang also referred to as tool.

While the pauses in between the words may seem a bit odd, there is a possibility of there being further meaning in these splits. By cutting the word esteem and bullet and only taking the second syllable which runs smoothly with the rest of the lyrics,we can make more sense of the pauses.

 With this pain inside of my chest
 Got no choice but to carry on, uh
 Carry on, life flies, so just carry on
 With this pain inside of my chest
 Got no choice but to carry on, uh
 Carry on, life flies, so just carry on
 With this pain inside of my chest
 Got no choice but to carry on, uh
 Yeah
tate_text:
A carry-on is a piece of luggage that airliners allow you to bring onto the plane. This could be an analogy to the baggage he once carried for quite some time as a result of the effects that lingered on with him because of the breakup with Geneva.

Chest pain is often a physical symptom of depression. Addressed throughout 17, X’s depression is likely caused by the heartbreak he’s experienced throughout his life, whether that be due to the deaths of friends and family members or accusations and relationship troubles.

Using clever wordplay, X is stating despite the issues he’s been through and the depression weighing him down, he’s gonna carry on with his life.

ref_text: Damn, son, where'd you find this?
tate_text:
“Damn son, where’d you find this?” is a mixtape drop created by Voice-over artist/ DJ Shadoe Haze. It became popular in the late 2000s on Gucci Mane and OJ da Juiceman’s Trap-A-Holics mixtapes.

In a December 2013 interview with Michael Fichman, Haze said of the drop:

There’s a little bitty town on the other side of West Monroe called Ruston. I have a guy that’s a close friend of mine that lives there. He produces dubstep and now he’s doing trap. He lives in that little bitty podunk town. That dude called me one day. I had no idea that drop had been out. […] That drop had been cut, it was just ad-libbed in a bunch of crap I sent out to a bunch of people.  Once it came out I couldn’t track down who the original client was because back then I wasn’t keeping in my library that I had ever done. He called me and said, ‘Hey, did you know that your voice is on this?’ I was like, ‘No, what are you talking about?; He sent me the link and he played it for me. I had no idea. He said 'this is like, everywhere.’ There are people around here who do know, but the average Joe that talks to me, even the people who listen to me on the radio—they don’t know. It cracks me up a little bit.

And I can't seem to shake this fuckin' feeling in my…
 Uh, cold shoulder, heartbroken, misspoken
tate_text:
The “cold shoulder” is a phrase to describe the act of disregarding someone. X interprets this saying in order to describe how everyone else completely ignored the fact that he was heartbroken from his past relationship with Geneva since he couldn’t express himself because of this.

This line also seemingly borrows another line from X’s earlier song, “King”.

Heartbroken, misspoken, breaking anything I touch

ref_text: Feelings I harbor? All this pent-up resentment I hold on to?
tate_text:
Matthew has a lot of reasons to hate Em (the original autograph snub, his role in Stan’s death), and that anger has just multiplied over the years. And carrying that much anger with you at all times is dangerous.

Notice the slight homophone with “pent” and “pen”. Matthew has been writing letters to Em out of anger while still holding some of it back.

“Harbor” may also foreshadow how he plans to kill him by dumping him in the ocean. Clever as ever

ref_text: Your lack of effort got me rappin' different
tate_text:
On this particular album, Drake uses different rapping styles, adding them to his more common rapping/singing style we all know. Worst Behavior, for example, is proof of a different, darker and more violent, style than what we normally expect from Drake.



Drake is bragging about how his talent allows him to cover different styles, unlike “effortless” rappers whose songs lack creativity in flow and content.

ref_text: In a state of bliss 'cause I said his goddamn name
tate_text:
In his interview with Sway, Eminem mentioned not wanting to give any more shine to Machine Gun Kelly, while still feeling the desire to respond to “Rap Devil”:

Now I’m in this fucking weird thing, because I’m like, ‘I gotta answer this motherfucker’. And every time I do that, it makes that person—as ‘irrelevant’ as people say I am in hip-hop—I make them bigger by getting into this thing, where I’m like, ‘I want to destroy him. But I also don’t want to make him bigger.’

Em expressed a similar sentiment on “The Ringer”:

You mention me, millions of views, attention in news
I mention you, lose-lose for me, win-win for you

On August 31, 2018, MGK popped a bottle of champagne to celebrate the attention from Eminem.

ref_text:
You love her, then you gotta give the world to her
 Is that a world tour or your girl's tour?
 I know that you gotta be a thug for her
 This ain't what she meant when she told you to open up more
tate_text:
In her song “Buy A Heart” from The Pinkprint, Nicki expressed both her desire for Meek and her fear of jumping into a relationship with him. She wasn’t sure if he was emotionally ready, and wanted him to “open up” to her.

Drake pokes fun at this, once again implying Nicki wears the pants both in their relationship and their business deals – he is merely the “opening act” on her Pinkprint Tour. Even then, he’s only one of many—Rae Sremmurd, Tinashe and DeJ Loaf appear on the tour as well. He’s opening up more alright, because he’s only the opening act.



Meek and Nicki confirmed their break up in January 2017. While Nicki was mature and respectful, Meek took a parting shot at her fashion sense.

ref_text:
Damn, death creepin' in my thoughts lately
 My one wish in this bitch, "Make it quick if the Lord take me"
 I know nobody meant to live forever anyway
tate_text:
In “For Whom The Bell Tolls,” Cole questions if he wants to continue living or not, despite the things he’s accomplished in the past years. It seems that death can’t leave his mind, so he wishes for it to be painless and quick.

Ain’t no way to live, do I wanna die?
I don’t know, I don’t know

Alternatively, this could be from his friend’s view, James, as much of this album is. If so, Cole reveals that James eventually dies on “Change.”

Heavy.

Amber Cole is a young woman from Alabama who earned notoriety in 2011 after a video of her performing oral sex on a classmate was widely distributed online. X also references J. Cole’s 2017 song “High For Hours,” where he rapped a whole verse about his conversation with former president Barack Obama at the My Brother’s Keeper Initiative.

Paranoid (Paranoid)
 Paranoid (P-paranoid)
 Paranoid (P-paranoid)
 But I see something in you (You're paranoid)
 Paranoid (Paranoid)
 Paranoid (P-paranoid)
 Paranoid (P-paranoid)
 But I see something in you
 (I see something in you)
tate_text:
The voice in the background is the track’s co-writer Lana Del Rey. Over and over she repeats the word “paranoid,” implying that even though he appears to enjoy this drug-riddled, sexually-charged lifestyle, he doesn’t feel completely safe or comfortable and is keeping his distance from relationships with women to protect himself.

After the previous dark but energy-filled lyrics, this conflict is sudden and highlighted by a beat change. As quick as his doubts started he realizes his life is full of “white lies” and falsehoods on his request and acknowledges he might just be paranoid about fame’s ill-effects. During the track, he has found a woman different from the others, mainly because she shares the same addictions as him. This provides a slight hope, and he returns to thanking God for his blessings.

ref_text:
Nigga, payback's a bitch, and bitch you been living in debt with me
 Dead 'em all, and especially, leave a call on his mother voicemail
 That say that he rest in peace,
tate_text:
The phrase “Payback’s a bitch” is used to describe how cruel karma can be when necessary. Payback is exactly what “living in debt” is in the first place—the condition of owing someone something. Kendrick is saying that all those who’ve wronged him are figuratively “living in payback debt” with him.

To pay up, it’s gonna cost them their life. They won’t need to worry about telling their parents, Kendrick’ll break the news to them on a voicemail. How generous!

ref_text:
Got me singing bout a bitch
 While I'm blowing out my steam
tate_text:
These are two of the three recurring themes on The Weeknd’s songs: women and drugs. He touches these topics not only because those are the things that he deals with on a regular basis but because his fans love that kind of music.

Being a artist comes with the disadvantage of working constantly so they need to blow out steam—a slang referring to relax—from time to time.

ref_text:
And when I'm over only pray
 That I flow from the bottom
 Closer to the top
 The higher that I climb
 The harder I'mma drop
tate_text:
The higher Abel gets on his drugs, the harder he will crash on his come down.

These lines also touch on his imminent climb in the music industry. Many artists sell out and “drop” lower quality music the more famous they become, eventually leading to the demise of their careers. However, The Weeknd has never been afraid of this commonality. He has touched on this topic in “Rolling Stone”, “The Fall”, and even in an open letter to his fans.

He has also acknowledged:

I’m not really scared of failing, because I already know what it means to be on the ground.

The narrator has become so addicted to his druggy habits that he can’t be content without them. Both depression and constant aggravation are common side affects of Marijuana withdrawals and he’s clearly going through both.

“My Saturdays are the loudest” is likely a play on “loud,” a term for potent weed. The narrator spends his weekends getting high, which repeats the cycle of withdrawal.



It’s worth noting that these lines correlate with the album’s release date of April 20th, also known as 4/20, a universally celebrated day dedicated to weed.

ref_text: A beacon of hope, put a B-I-R-D in the air
tate_text:
Similar to a “wing and a prayer,” a “beacon of hope” is a notion used for something that sets a positive precedent – in this case, Eminem was the beacon of hope for young and emerging rappers, particularly those who were white, or wanted to rap about more sensitive, controversial topics.

Eminem could be referring to the concept of “flipping the bird” more commonly noted as giving the finger or more specifically, the middle one. This gesture would be indicative of Eminem putting the bird in the air to all those who doubted him, his legacy and/or undermined his global reach.  Someone more important than me? (Someone more important than me?)
tate_text:
As Cole welcomes his child into this world, he begins to question whether or not he is truly worthy of the monumental task that is being a father. For humans, and for most organic life, the most basic instinct is that of self preservation. Thus, our brains are automatically hardwired to make decisions that our in our own best interest. Yet, Cole recognizes, like all new parents, that as a father in certain situations he will have to put his daughter’s well being above his own.

This is a monumental moment in the album, as Cole’s newfound appreciation and understanding of fatherhood largely shape his final reflections on the life of his slain friend James and what made him a “real nigga.”

My watch came, niggas can't wait for one of these
 I see you nigga, this ain't no Rolex, it's a AP nigga
 I'm hot, dog, catch up to me nigga—uh, couldn't resist
tate_text:
I’m hot, dog, catch up with me nigga.

Hot dawg = Catch up or Hotdog = Ketchup

Cole’s clearly playing with words here. First, he means that he’s a top dawg, try to be on his level or try to catch up. Second, he’s implying that he’s literally a hotdog. What goes well with hotdogs? Ketchup, yes.

Finally, the phrase “Couldn’t resist,” takes the conclusion that Cole couldn’t resist inserting/making puns, silly puns. Plainly, this shows Cole being funny.

Although flawless diamonds do exist, they’re exceedingly rare. Most diamonds have flaws or “inclusions.” Beyonce compares their love to a diamond—it has flaws but it’s still incredibly valuable, and its purity gives it strength.

One of Jay’s most famous symbols is the Dynasty sign, usually provoked by Jay saying “Throw them diamonds up.”



Although it’s incredibly hard to chip diamond, flawless or pure diamonds are considered the hardest natural material on Earth.

ref_text: Mr. Jefferson, welcome home
tate_text:
Rather than interrupting Jefferson’s flow (like a certain someone else), Washington is happy to go along; he would rather unify than divide.

Historically, Jefferson and Washington had a complex relationship, which devolved during the 1790s. In the famous Mazzei letter,  Jefferson suggests that Washington has become a weakling serving England’s interests. At one point in the letter, Jefferson states, “It would give you a fever, if I should name the apostates who have embraced these heresies; men who were Solomons in council, and Sampsons in combat, but whose hair has been cut off by the whore England."

 That can only mean one thing

 That can only mean one thing
tate_text:
Drake knows that at this time of night, there’s only one person who’ll call him. He also knows that the only thing she’ll want is to come over and have sex. By describing his cell phone as a hotline, he’s referencing phone sex hotlines that people call “for a good time.”

Notably, Drake is using “bling” as the sound of his phone ringing. Drake’s mentor Lil Wayne originally coined the ideophone “bling bling” as a sound that could adequately express the flash of jewelry. Also worth noting that rings are jewelry, cellphone ring = bling. Wow!

Slate wrote about Drake’s love-hate relationship with communications technology and even said “he’s claimed the laurels of the 21st-century bard of telephony.”

tate_text:
This is the start of the verse of which is from Jermaine’s (J Cole’s) view, opposed to the rest of the song which is from his friend James McMillan Jr. who died at the age of 22. James McMillan Jr. is mentioned not only in this song but at the end of changes where Jermaine reminisced on when he found out that his friend had died.

Jermaine describes a vivid memory within this verse about his last conversation with James before he died at the age of 22, when he tells him about how he wasn’t given enough time to make his amends but praises his only daughter as his greatest accomplishment.

This line is the start of the conversation between the two on the phone, just before James opens up to Jermaine about his life and feelings.

ref_text: Wasn’t the trouble with much of our previous government size?
tate_text:
This refers to the British Empire, which was the government Jefferson and the other revolutionaries previously lived under. In terms of literal size, the British Empire was known for nearly overtaking the populated surface of the planet at one point in time, and administration of that vast population was difficult to oversee. It might also refer to the British government itself, which was heavily bureaucratic and often needlessly complicated and insular.

Madison is also betraying a bit of his Democratic Republican bias here, as his party was more in favor of a decentralized government that gave more power to the citizens and states and less power to the federal government. Seeing Federalists like Hamilton propose these huge federal-level undertakings would have sent a chill down his spine.

Lin wrote in Hamilton: The Revolution (p. 199):

Madison used to have his own verse, wherein he said: ‘I used to write with him/Imbibe with him and ride with him/I find myself on this side of a sizable divide with him./We used to fight for the right to be left alone./But left alone to his own devices, he’s a crisis all his own.’ Ended up cutting everything but these lines, as a lead-in to the group verse.

ref_text: Teamed up with the CCA
tate_text:
Today, there are more African-American adults under correctional control than were enslaved in 1850, before the Civil War.

The explosion in the size of our prison population over the last 40 years rakes in billions of dollars a year for CCA and other for-profit prison companies. The United States has built up the highest incarceration rate of any country in the world, with over 2.3 million men and women living behind bars. This is a historical anomaly; despite relatively stable incarceration rates earlier in the twentieth century, our prison population grew by 700% between 1970 and 2005, far outpacing both crime and general population growth.

And this overincarceration epidemic has a massive and disproportionate impact on people of color. If current trends continue, 1 in 3 Black men born today can expect to serve time behind bars.

More about Kanye’s CCA lyric is here: http://www.aclu.org/blog/prisoners-rights-racial-justice/kanye-west-new-slaves-and-long-tradition-locking-people-profit

And you can read all about the growth and shameful practices of CCA and other private prison companies in Banking on Bondage, our report, here: http://www.aclu.org/prisoners-rights/banking-bondage-private-prisons-and-mass-incarceration

This is something one of his friends would say to him. “Get it together homie, smash this chick one time and lose her.” Stick to the G code.

This line like many others in this track has a double meaning. The obvious one is explained above, but continuing on the double meaning theme of the song this is also directed at rap (or rap game). By “Fuck her one time and be through with forever” he explains the mentality of many rappers out today that are openly only in the game for the money. Get your money and run…

ref_text:
Hit the prez with a Cuban link on my neck
 Uneducated, but I got a million-dollar check like that
tate_text:
Less than a year after making this boast, Kendrick would find himself invited for a one-on-one with Obama in the Oval Office, in which they spoke about Kendrick’s work with children, racial issues, and—just maybe— the president’s favorite song of the year.



Kendrick is definitely wearing a chain in their meeting, but it appears to be a bit more modest than the broader style of the classic Cuban link.

The second line, as referenced in the Genius interview with Kendrick about this album, shows how Kendrick is deeply troubled by the fact that in today’s school system, kids are taught about many things which they will never need in life but not about important, practical life lessons such as handling money and paying taxes. This plays into the song and the album as a whole, as Wesley Snipes is the example given in this song of someone who wasn’t educated on what they could and could not do with taxes and suffered the consequences.

ref_text: I'll ask again—oops, accident
tate_text:
Kendrick stopping his verse and saying “oops” is reminiscent of one of his biggest influences, Lil Wayne.

Wayne has similar lines on songs like “Stuntin”  and “Ransom”:


People ask me if I pray, I say, “Yeah, once in a blue moon”
Oops I mean a red moon, I did it again Tune

You ain’t heard of me then you should go and get a Blue’s Clue?
Oops! I mean a red clue


Kendrick spoke about his love for Wayne in an interview with Coveteur:

Lil Wayne is the greatest. Not only because of his music but also because of the culture he put behind it. It was a big part of what he was talking about, so we always hold Lil Wayne in high regards.

Drake’s making sufficient sums of money for fake people to come out of the woodwork and act like they knew him back when he was up-and-coming.

He’s previously mentioned how people try to use him – such as in the “Say What’s Real” freestyle:

And don’t listen to anybody that knew me
Cause to have known me would
Mean that there’s a new me
And if you think I changed in the slightest
Could of fooled me

ref_text: I'll do it for you niggas and do it for myself
tate_text:
Not only is Drake killing the rap game himself, he has also been the “go-to guy” for up-and-coming artists trying to make a name for themselves. Among the artists that Drake has helped catapult towards the mainstream through featured verses or cosigns: The Weeknd, Future, A$AP Rocky, Migos, and ILoveMakonnen.



Now with his own record label, Drake has begun to breed his own roster of talented artists, most notably Majid Jordan, featured on the smash hit single “Hold On We’re Going Home”, and OB O'Brien.

A house divided against itself cannot stand. I believe this government cannot endure, permanently, half slave and half free. I do not expect the Union to be dissolved — I do not expect the house to fall — but I do expect it will cease to be divided.

While he’s referencing slavery and the emancipation, he appropriates Lincoln’s speech to serve the black community – they must stand united.

ref_text: Staying up all night, order me pad thai
tate_text:
Pad thai is a popular dish that originates from Thailand. It consists of stir-fried rice noodles. In a 2014 Mirror interview, Ariana stated that she was adhering to a vegan diet. Ordering in delivery is meant to conjure up images of a low-key couple just staying in together.

This line is reminiscent of a lyric from Mac Miller’s 2016 song “Cinderella”—a song which Ariana confirmed was about her in a May 2018 Twitter post:

And when you hungry, I can chef you up some stir fry

ref_text:
‘Cause I don't write shit, ‘cause I ain't got time
 ‘Cause my seconds, minutes, hours go to the almighty dollar
 And the almighty power of that ch-cha-cha-chopper
tate_text:
Important to note that he’s saying he doesn’t write down his lyrics. Not that he doesn’t come up with them himself. But why doesn’t he write? One could understand from these lines that it’s because writing is a non-revenue-generating waste of his time. He’s too busy a) making money, and b) shooting machine guns (commonly refered to as “choppers”).

These lines also contain a religious motif — tablet (10 commandments), sacrificing time to the “almighty” dollar, praising “almighty” power.

ref_text:
'Cause no one oversees these cops and
 All we see is 'em beat charges
tate_text:
Em questions the accountability of the police force. Despite the presence of bodycam footage and intense media scrutiny, the number of policemen who face serious consequences for police brutality are still statistically low.

As reported by CNN:

Between 2005 and April 2017, 80 officers have been arrested on murder or manslaughter charges for on-duty shootings. During that 12-year span, 35% were convicted, while the rest were pending or not convicted.

More specifically, regarding Freddie Gray, referenced earlier in the song:

Three of the six officers involved were acquitted of all charges, including one of murder. Prosecutors also dropped all charges against three other officers, ending one of the most closely watched and unsuccessful police prosecutions in the nation. [x]

ref_text:
Yeah (For your eyes)
 For your eyes only (For your eyes)
 For your eyes only, for your eyes only
 (For your eyes, for your eyes)
 For your eyes only
tate_text:
As a popular fan theory suggested, and Dreamville producer Elite later confirmed, the large majority of this album is not from Cole’s perspective. Instead, Cole largely wrote from the perspective of a dead friend, whom he gave the fictional name of James in the interest of protecting the privacy of his family.

Throughout the song and early in the album, Cole expresses from the perspective of James a feeling of inevitable demise inspired by the precarious life he felt he had no choice but to lead. In the end, James asks only that Cole preserve and tell his story to his daughter if he really should meet his untimely demise.

Unfortunately, as Cole reveals on “Change”, James' life is violently cut short, and Cole fulfills his wish to tell his story to his daughter by writing this album. Thus, the album is truly not written to really be understood or consumed by his fans or critics, but instead, for James' daughter, or as he expresses it, “For your eyes only.”

ref_text:
I never fantasize 'bout murder 'cause I'm still sane
 But I can't seem to fight this urge to make you feel pain
 I know that vengeance is the Lord's and it's not for me
tate_text:
Struggling with the thought of this person not facing the consequences for their actions, but also not being able to bear the thought of murdering them, Cole references Romans 12:19, how he shouldn’t be worried about vengeance.

19 Beloved, never avenge yourselves, but leave it to the wrath of God, for it is written, “Vengeance is mine, I will repay, says the Lord.”

Rather, he should be more focused on repaying this person with love and blessing, as commanded to in 1 Peter 3:9:

9 Do not repay evil for evil or reviling for reviling, but on the contrary, bless, for to this you were called, that you may obtain a blessing.

In an interview with No Jumper, Cole shared his thoughts about religion, particularly Christianity, and some of his experiences with faith throughout his life:

It hit a point where I had to question it for the first time. I felt bad about it. I felt guilty …for even having a negative thought about it. I went and got baptized, started reading The Bible, and I was scared as fuck. Then it hit a point in my life where I just fell off and said, “I’ll let the answer come.” As I got older, I felt like I got a personal understanding of what God is to me, a strong belief too.

This is not the first time Cole has talked about God in his music, talking about it in songs such as “Change.”

Most niggas don’t believe in God and so they terrified
It’s either that or they be fearing they gon' go to Hell
Asking the Father for forgiveness, got ‘em overwhelmed (Please, God, I want to go to Heaven)

Also mentioning “the Lord” on “Love Yourz.”

Though I’m not sure what’s ‘bout to happen next
I asked for strength from the Lord up above

ref_text: My Roc, flawless
tate_text:
In contrast to the literal “rock” (ie. diamond) of the previous lines, the music video indicates that this is a reference to the Roc (Roc-A-Fella Records and now Roc Nation) and a nod to Bey’s husband and Roc-A-Fella/Roc Nation founder Jay Z. Husbands are also sometimes compared to rocks, as the backbone of the traditional family unit.

The melody and phrasing of the song’s hook, especially this section, and particularly Beyoncé’s intonation on the word “Roc”, bare many similarities to the melody and lyrics of the traditional American spiritual “Sinnerman”, made perhaps most famous by Nina Simone.

ref_text:
And you could take it to the bank and deposit that
 Put your two cents in and get a dollar back
tate_text:
“Two cents” is an idiom for ideas or thoughts that one contributes to a topic or discussion.

Here, Wayne suggests that you “make an investment” by sharing your ideas and that you can earn a return from it.  The bank may serve as metaphor the rap business, meaning then that if you want to convey your lyrics in rap form, people may be receptive of it and you can earn money back from putting something out there that you were worried may not be beneficial, such as saying something controversial or uninteresting.

ref_text: Have it all, lose it all
tate_text:
During the course of the second act Hamilton is at the height of his career; he has power in the American government, support from George Washington, is able to pass his financial plan and his family is thriving.

However he also loses everything in this act; his political power, his reputation, his son, his marriage and most importantly, his life.

This also relates to “Wait For It”, when Burr reflects that Hamilton has nothing to lose-this is not true anymore; Hamilton has it all and will lose it all now.

ref_text: Love yourself, girl, or nobody will
tate_text: This single line encompasses the entire message of the song: if you don’t have the security to admire yourself for your own sake, then you’ll never be able to maintain a stable relationship with someone else long enough for them to love you. That same insecurity will also lead to you not believing them when they tell you about your good qualities rather than your bad ones.

ref_text: Gonna be that one? And then once we get 'em, it's never the same
tate_text:
When people fall in love, all sorts of ideals are created and projected onto the ones that they love – until it is slowly realized the individual with which they fell in love with does not in the slightest meet those ideals

In reference to drug addiction, once someone gets addicted, he/she remembers the high the drug created and hopes to create it again by acquiring it again, but with continuous use, the highs created require more and more of the drug – meaning the original amount of the drug does not live up to the hopes of the addict.
When you get the person back after losing him/her, that person who comes back is never the same neither are you.

He could be talking about the hiphop world also. Like in the song “Almost Famous”, he said he always want to be famous, but when he’s already famous (like recently) he felt like it’s not as what he thought it would feel like. He lost his freedom (like in the song “Marshall Mathers” or “25 to life”)

ref_text: I’ll write my way out…
tate_text:
This line is important in its own right, as it can both show a bit of Hamilton’s character and talent. The poor boy has been through so much, from his parents leaving him (both either on purpose or because of death) to a hurricane that destroyed nearly everything.

   One, he’s trying to recreate the miracle that got him out of the hopeless situation that got him to the place in society he is in right now. He’s essentially saying: “Hey! Look! I’m good at writing so I should be excused for cheating on my wife, it’s all good!”

   However, this method doesn’t work, as the last hurricane he was in wasn’t his own fault. He used his wit and talent to get out of it, he’s trying to use the same strategy to make his way out of the metaphorical “hurricane” he created. He wrote down honesty both times. First, honesty with his feelings, second, honesty with the situation. Telling everyone you cheated on your wife won’t get you out of your metaphorical hurricane.

   Two, he’s showing his character off. He is stubborn. Stubborn beyond belief. Even with everyone in the back of his mind telling him to calm down, to let it go, that his mistakes will be recorded, and that he should just learn when to be patient.

   The woman he loves, a member of her family which he claimed to care about, the very woman that had to put up with the person who turned him into a scandal, and one of the last people he could have called a friend if he tried to fix their relationship all telling him to just calm down. Even when the rest of the company joins in, he still does nothing. He does nothing to listen to them. He believes his intelligence is superior to them, and therefore doesn’t listen to the nagging voices in the back of his head to calm down.

   In the workshop for Hurricane, Hamilton acknowledges Laurens would definitely not approve, with the line “The friend who would tell me not to do it is in the ground.” However, he still continues. Such a stubborn character.

ref_text: ‘Cause you dicks butt kiss,
tate_text:
Em uses some great word-play here,

Sticking with the football wordplay, Dick Butkus was a feared linebacker for the Chicago Bears in the 60’s and 70’s.



The Beastie Boys were the originators of this pun. It was first used by Ad-Rock on the song “Get On the Mic”/“B-Boy Bouillabaisse” from Paul’s Boutique:

You say “fuck that”, yo holmes, fuck this
I’m the King Ad-whammy, you’re Dick Butkis

Asher Roth uses this pun on his 2009 album. Em disses Ash one song later in Asshole.

White rappers seem have a thing for this.

ref_text:
Jam a Crest Whitestrip in the tip of my dick
 With an ice pick, stick it in a vise grip
 Hang it on a spike fence, bang it with a pipe wrench
tate_text:
“Crest Whitestrips” are teeth whiteners that commonly irritate or cause increased sensitivity to one’s gums/teeth. So imagine how it must feel to have one jammed down one’s “dick with an ice pick.” Em goes on to describe other ways to mutilate his genitals, such as using a “vise grip” which essentially is a wrench that can tightly lock something in place; in this instance, Em’s dick on top of a “spike fence,”  (pictured below).



From the beginning of his career to present,  Em has rapped about his own genital mutilation. Back in 1999’s The Slim Shady LP, he raps on “Role Model”:

I tie a rope around my penis and jump from a tree
You probably wanna grow up to be just like me

These bars aren’t simply for gruesome shock value, as Em later goes on to explain he’d rather endure such agony than “hear you on a mic,” referring to the aforementioned mumble rappers earlier in the verse.

ref_text: I'm racin', I'm pacin', I stand and I sit
tate_text:
He’s so worked up and agitated that he can’t stay in one place. So he’s moving around considerably because he doesn’t know where to aim his frustration. Hopefully you’re not on the other end when he explodes.



Also, note the wordplay stemming from the previous lyrics (“cause they driving me crazy”) – driving and racing are associated.

ref_text: You haven’t met him yet, you haven’t had the chance
tate_text:
In this line, and the above line “You ready for more yet,” Burr breaks to fourth wall to reaffirm his role as narrator. This could also be directed at Hamilton, who meets Jefferson in this number.

Additionally, this line employs a level of misdirection in the sense that the audience has indeed met Jefferson in a more concrete sense through the actor playing him, Daveed Diggs, who plays Marquis de Lafayette in the first act. In an interview with Charlie Rose, Diggs explains the double casting:

It was conceived that way. Lin always said that it was because we had to meet these people fresh in the second act so you want to hopefully have the audience have already fallen in love with the actor so you don’t have to build up a relationship with the new character. You don’t have to spend as much time doing that.

“Cold thumb” refers to ignoring someone’s text, sort of like giving someone the cold shoulder. As time goes by the likeness of this person will disappear and Kendrick, because of his pride, will ignore this person.

Despite Kanye’s claims of being real, Cole takes a look at the people Mr. West surrounds himself with and only sees fake, starting with the Kardashian clan and their “reality show”. It seems as though every member of the Kardashians, including Kanye’s wife Kim, has dealt with some sort of accusation of being fake, be it lip injections, implants, butt injections, or even the accusation that Kim’s Paris robbery was a fake.



Furthermore, no one in Kanye’s camp seems to want to point out the problems going on with his life. Instead, they are content to sit back and watch him unravel, claiming it’s just part of his “genius.” Ye seems to recognize this himself, as The Life of Pablo had songs like “Real Friends” and “Wolves” which are both about being around fake people.

ref_text:
Feelin' like an animal with these cameras all in my grill
 Flashin' lights, flashin' lights
tate_text:
The constant flashes of paparazzi cameras make her feel like a zoo animal – an attraction for others' entertainment, at the sacrifice of her freedom.

Even zoo animals get fed up with the cameras sometimes: Felix the polar bear (shown below) once had his way with an expensive camera that a visitor dropped into his enclosure at a zoo in Nuremberg, Germany.



Beyoncé’s “brother”-in-law Kanye West has used lights – including flashing ones – as a leitmotif for fame throughout his music. In fact, in Kanye’s remix of this song, the “flashing lights” line is interrupted by a sample from Ye’s “Flashing Lights”.

ref_text:
Now I got a house in LA, now I got a bigger pool than Ye
 And look man, Ye’s pool is nice, mine's just bigger's what I’m saying
 I’m that nigga’s what I’m saying
tate_text:
Drake’s LA house is massive, and at around 75,000 square feet it should put in perspective everything he’s done in his career. However, the thing he turns to as signal of success is the size of the pool. In an interview with Rolling Stone he said:

I’m obsessed with, like, residential pools. One of my goals in life is to have the biggest residential pool on the planet.

Along with the Jay Z reference above, this playful jab is Drizzy’s way of comparing himself to hip hop legends. Kanye himself has at least one braggadocios line about his pool.



Drake’s pool on the left, Kanye’s on the right

Cock up is Patois for prop up.

The patois influence on this album is an homage to the heavy West Indian population in parts of Toronto.

tate_text:
J. Cole is known to shy from the spot light. He isn’t the type to flare up in response to another rapper dissing him, in an interview with New York Times, Cole said

For so long my mind state was, I have to show how much better than the next man I am through these bars. Who’s the best? Let me prove it. And it’s just like, damn, I’m really feeding into a cycle of keeping black people down, I’m really feeding into that.

Though this may have changed on another track from this album, 1985 ( intro to the “Fall off”), where he allegedly responds to rapper Lil' Pump’s disses toward Cole

 When Cole says he can’t tolerate disloyalty, he can also mean his step dad cheating as mentioned on “Once an Addict”. His stepdad’s name is also Edward, hence the name “kiLL edward”

tate_text:
Weed is known for relaxing the human body and mind, while money (argued by many) makes you happy.  However, despite X having a net worth of $2 million, he still can’t find the remedy for his broken heart, which is probably why he doesn’t even finish the word “alright” here.  As most of us know by now, this song, like many others, is likely alluding to his ex-girlfriend Geneva Ayala, who cheated on him and accused him of assaulting her.  X is trying to find a way to recover from the heartbreak she caused him.

In the first and only verse of this song, X says:

I’m sadder than most of y'all with the money and the freedom, nigga
What is money really worth if it ain’t love?

These lines only show that money isn’t making X happy–he needs love.

This could also be a reference to the Kendrick Lamar song, “Alright.” Kendrick co-signed X’s debut album, 17.

Cole remembers a point of time when he was at a club near his hometown in Fayetteville, and gang-members he knew would have disputes with other people and they would open gunfire and shoot up the scene.

However, he plays on the words “shooting up” to his homeboy who sold drugs, referencing “shooting up” drugs, such as common narcotics like heroin into your veins, to the scene of the gang members shooting gunfire onto the scene.

Toward the end of the verse, you here Cole’s voice shifting, alluding to Cole’s alter ego, “​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​kiLL edward” to show how he would’ve dealt with the pain.

ref_text:
How can I tell you I'm making a killin'?
 You made me a killer, emancipation of a real nigga
tate_text:
Kendrick references Abraham Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation – which freed enslaved blacks in Confederate states during the Civil War. Slavery was not constitutionally abolished until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in 1865. However, even after the Thirteenth, Fourteenth (natural-born US citizenship), and Fifteenth (Voting Rights) Amendments were ratified, the white South still used fear to oppress the black population. Black Codes, Jim Crow laws, the Ku Klux Klan’s extralegal violence, poll taxes, Plessy v. Ferguson, sharecropping, and many other obstacles prevented the black population from exercising their constitutional rights.

He describes the cycle where white America sees his people as a violent uncontrollable “nigga” and thus condemns them, through laws and law enforcement, to being stuck in this self-perpetuating loop.

Carrying on from his sentiment on “Dig A Hole”, he throws the challenge down to the multitude of rappers who were taking shots at him at the time (the list is always long and illustrious).

One of Jay’s favourite take-downs is to debase his competitor so they feel less “grown” or important as him. Calling it “silly nonsense” makes it sound childish.



Squashing unnecessary beef is mature.

ref_text: My manager back in the days was racist
tate_text:
He suggests by the following line that, in this line, he is referring to the manager he had as a teenager working at a skating rink.

He has since moved on to Mark Pitts, who has managed Biggie and Nas, and now also manages Miguel, who’s collaborated with Cole on “All I Want is You” and “Power Trip”.

Mark seems to respect Cole for his artistry and personal qualities. He had this to say:

I was going to stop managing hip-hop. I’d been through so much, from Big to Shyne to Nas. But J.Cole brought me back. It wasn’t just how he was an artist. Seeing where his head was at was a pleasure; it made me want to take him to another level.

ref_text: I'm tryna put you in the worst mood, ah
tate_text:
Though the song carries a palpable swagger, Abel states immediately that this is not a song to make us feel good. By proclaiming later in the hook, “Look what you’ve done” he implicates his consumers/audience, suggesting we’re complicit in cosigning him to the material excess and emotional disconnection he’s built his career off of.

The sentiment here is deeply reminiscent of Abel’s song “Kiss Land” from his debut studio album of the same name. In the outro of the song, after solemnly considering all of his half empty new possessions like “a brand new place” he’s seen “twice all year”, he somberly and repeatedly croons to the listener “this ain’t nothing to relate to.” Both there and here, he shares the pain and emptiness he still feels even behind all of his accolades and possessions and urges us to stop praising and desiring his lifestyle as he’s become aware of the darkness that comes with it.

ref_text: See
tate_text:
Whoops, we already did some “see” rhymes in this song, didn’t we?

By this point, you might be getting the sense that poor King George is not very good at this music-writing thing. The rhyme scheme in this song is mostly very simple: pairs of (mostly long) lines with short rhyming words at the end. These rhymes are straightforward and mostly monosyllabic: “say”/“pay”, “cry”/“by”, “sad”/“mad”. In fact, all of the language George uses is simple and straightforward; “estrangement” is the most difficult word. When properly punctuated, the lyrics are at roughly a fourth-grade reading level.

George only has one line with internal rhymes, and those rhymes are defective in two ways. Firstly, the “tea”/“sea” rhyme is actually appropriated from Alexander Hamilton in “Farmer Refuted”, who also used it in a far more sophisticated way to discuss the Boston Tea Party (“Why should a tiny island across the sea regulate the price of tea?”)

Secondly, the “sea”/“see” rhyme is an example of a “rich rhyme”, a rhyme of homophones. Rich rhymes are highly valued in the poetry of other languages, particularly French, but English poetry disfavors them.

“Arrangement”/“estrangement” and “draining”/“complaining” aren’t too bad, and he deploys non-musical rhetorical devices (particularly repetition) very nicely, but compared to the other characters in this show, George is simply not up to par. Nine-year-old Philip does better.

It’s almost like hereditary inheritance doesn’t necessarily put the most talented people in the spotlight, isn’t it?

ref_text:
'Cause you're a good girl and you know it
 I know exactly who you could be
tate_text:
Deep down, this girl is good and Drake can see who she really is. He wants to bring that out of her.

In what is assuredly not a coincidence, Drake has had past real-life dealings with a certain good girl gone bad.

Drake’s interest helping his romantic interests—like helping his girl realize her full potential—comes up a lot in his work. Whether he’s worrying about a girl being lonely in a new city or feels bad for the 26-and-older girls who can’t maintain friendships—Drake stays concerned. He’s also known to use the romantic interests in his songs as a way to talk to himself—something he mentioned in his interview with Elliot Wilson.

ref_text: Y'all niggas trappin' so lack-sical-daisy
tate_text:
“Lackadaisical” is a term that means lacking enthusiasm, apathetic, or lazy. Cole is speaking on the laziness of the current rap scene with the rise of mumble rappers and trap music in recent years whose subject matter is strictly drugs, women, and money. Notice how he enunciates the word lackadaisical incorrectly as if to make him sound lazy and uncaring like trap rappers do when they mispronounce words.

Cole would express almost identical thoughts on KOD’s final track, “1985 (Intro to the ‘Fall Off’)”:

Now you scramblin' and hopin' to get hot again
But you forgot you only popped ‘cause you was ridin’ trends
Now you old news and you goin' through regrets
‘Cause you never bought that house, but you got a Benz
And a bunch of jewels and a bunch of shoes
And a bunch of fake friends, I ain’t judgin’ you

Interestingly, the use of “lackadaisical” displays Cole’s lyrical uniqueness since no other rapper would even bother to match his vocabulary level.

ref_text:
Now you see why I don't sleep, not even a wink, I don't blink
 I don't doze off, I don't even nod to the beats
 I don't even close my fuckin' eyes when I sneeze
tate_text:
Eminem uses several examples to show that he’s always got his eyes open, including a play on words and a subject of continued interest.

First, Eminem makes a play on the expression “[to] nod off.” “Nodding off” is an expression for falling asleep, as the head slowly droops as someone loses consciousness, mimicking a slow nod. It’s noteworthy that nodding along to a beat doesn’t necessarily mean that one’s eyes are closed.

Additionally, Em claims that he doesn’t even close his eyes when he sneezes. Most people close their eyes when they sneeze as an automatic reflex. It is also a longstanding myth that one’s eyes will pop out of their head if they were to sneeze with their eyes open.

ref_text:
The way I kissed your scars
 The way I fixed your heart, oh
tate_text:
In “Call Out My Name”, The Weeknd admitted to both him and Selena being scarred and broken:

We found each other
I helped you out of a broken place

The Weeknd helped her by — though being callous himself– loving her and in a way, fixing her heart instead of suffering.

“Kissing one’s scars” has a double meaning. It means that he loved her and accepted her “true colors” and for who she is—he comforted her emotional scars. Additionally, this could mean that Abel kissed Selena’s literal scars that she received after her kidney transplant surgery to treat her Lupus diagnosis.



This may also be referring to a similar lyric from one of Tesfaye’s previous songs, “As You Are”:

”Show me your broken heart and all your scars…”

Again, he could be alluding to how he recognised Selena’s pain and scarring after her past separation from Justin Bieber and, as a result, managed to help her move on out of her heartbreak.
