ref_text: But I won’t apologize for doing what’s right
tate_text:
This is a direct call back to the events leading up to the death of his son. George Eacker wouldn’t apologize to Philip Hamilton for what he said about Alexander and Philip died in that confrontation. He tells Philip to avoid a duel at all costs, but Hamilton doesn’t follow his own advice.

Here, Alexander doesn’t apologize for what he said (directly mirroring Eacker’s non-apology) and thus this dispute now merits “further action” from Burr. He cuts off an avenue of resolution that’s been drilled into our heads twice now regarding the rules of duelling, and so leads himself into his final confrontation.

ref_text: A system he can shape however he wants
tate_text:
Hamilton, Jefferson, and Madison participated in one of the first documented occasions of “log rolling”, where votes are exchanged in Congress between two legislators – or the quid pro quo (“something for something” in Latin) that Madison mentions later in the song.

Specifically, the Dinner Compromise of 1790 negotiations lead to Madison lending support to pass the Funding Act of 1790 and Hamilton lending support to move the capital to somewhere along the Potomac to the current location, Washington D.C..

The Funding Act of 1790 essentially allowed the national government to take in and manage state debts. Northern states, which were in a numerable amount of debt, favored the plan because it would alleviate their debts. Southern states were not in as much debt due to their profitable agrarian industry and felt outrage towards the act because they, in short, would be paying for the Northern states debts if the act was to pass.

It wasn’t quite handing all the reins to Hamilton, but the Compromise approved the most important aspect of his financial plan.

ref_text: Love get confused in the mind of a child
tate_text: Cole’s referencing how his “love” can be confusing to naive onlookers who claim if he really loved his wife, he wouldn’t have cheated. A child would say the next line “love wouldn’t lie”, whereas many adults– specifically those who have cheated– will tell you that they love their partner and their infidelity is not proof that they don’t love their spouse, but rather their inability to resist temptation. So, the mind of a child can confuse love as something that automatically stops a person from cheating, where adult minds know that the love and cheating may not be mutually exclusive, and that the idea that one automatically becomes faithful when they find a spouse and get their “happily ever after” is naive.

This is a form of antanaclasis (a stylistic scheme of repeating a word with a different meaning). Em breaks down the word finish line to a “line” in rap terms, and uses “finish” as a verb instead.

The finish line can represent:


THE TOP SPOT, which is Eminem’s, and ultimately every other rapper’s, goal in the industry; to be the best and most respected.
RETIREMENT. Similar to Jay Z, we’re coming up on the 10th anniversary of Eminem’s intended retirement date, 2004’s Encore (Jay-Z intended to retire after 2003’s The Black Album. The rap game has proven to be addictive for both artists, as both continue to make millions off their trade.
On a grimmer note, DEATH. Then these “lines that he finishes” could double as lines of cocaine, meaning that he can see death approaching every time he uses. After all, even though he’s sober, this entire album is a revisitation of the past, and as the first single this would encapsulate that.

tate_text:
According to Elite, Cole rented a house in North Carolina for all of the Dreamville artists and producers to create music in an isolated environment. It’s located in a predominantly white neighborhood and the neighbors soon became suspicious there might be drug related activity connected to the house and eventually the SWAT team was brought in to investigate.

It’s also in the suburbs of a pretty wealthy neighborhood in North Carolina. So you have, predominately, African-Americans coming in and out of this house. Ubers coming, and every once in awhile you’ll see a group of us outside on the porch smoking weed. So the neighbors started getting real paranoid.

ref_text:
We're gonna be alright
 We're gonna be alright
 We're gonna be alright
tate_text:
Ariana reminds her friend, lover, and anyone else listening that if you’re going through a hard time, things are falling apart, or the love you’ve been seeking isn’t working out, don’t worry too much because everything is going to work out in the end.

In Grande’s case, she went through a public breakup with Big Sean and received widespread backlash after she was filmed licking un-sold donuts at a store in Lake Elsinore, California in 2015. However, she’s weathered the storm and bounced back in 2016, cracking jokes on SNL and gearing up to release a new album.

On her breakup with Big Sean, she had some wise words that echo the message of this song:

I’m not going to pretend I have great breakup advice. It’s hard. Good luck. You’ll be fine. You don’t need anyone. It’s nice to have someone that makes you happy, but it’s nice to be happy on your own as well.

ref_text:
You was never gang, gang, gang, gang, you was never one of us
 Had us fooled for a minute there, now we done all grown up
 But I’m better off anyway, y’all never gon’ finish Drake
tate_text:
Drake uses the Scarborough slang “Gang, gang, gang, gang,” which is chanted in repetition to depict how close knit of a crew you are, while  borrowing Tory Lanez’s flow of repeating words in his verses to add emphasis. He does this on his single “B.L.O.W.:”

Hate to be the reason
Why your dream bitches never get to see ya
Never, ever, ever, ever, ever
Me forever, ever, ever, ever, ever?

In an interview with HipHopDX back in 2014, Tory spoke about how Drake helped to put Toronto on the map and the influence he had on the growth of his music:

I feel like in Toronto, we’ve always tried to have a particular sound, and I feel like Drake happened to be one of the dudes that paved that sound. […] I feel like [Drake has] helped me piece my sound together, and I feel like subconsciously, as an artist, you’re gonna take certain things from what you hear on a day-to-day basis.

However, once Drake got bigger and started separating himself from his Toronto peers, artists like Tory started to show dislike. Drake noticed this and realized Tory’s true feelings towards him. It goes to show that Drake will stick to his “No New Friends” policy and focus on his business.

Associate turned enemy Quentin Miller claimed this line was directed at him, responding his own track “unHoly:”

I was never Gang Gang
I was 1317 the whole time

tate_text:
Nicki takes on the voice of her critics in these two lines. They complain about her fake character, claiming she puts on this face for her fans but in reality is like a diet cheater, stuffing cheesecake into her pants.

There is a double meaning here as cheese is another term for money. Her pockets are fat (rich) while she remains skinny and successful, like Barbie.

ref_text: My city love me like Mac Dre in the Bay
tate_text:
Mac Dre is a legendary rapper representing the city of Vallejo in the northern region of the San Francisco Bay Area. From maintaining his status as an independent artist throughout his career and recording albums from a prison pay phone to being a pioneer of the Thizz Movement and personification of the Hyphy Movement prior to his passing in 2004, Mac Dre had a major impact on the substance and style of the Bay Area hip-hop culture—as Bay Area rapper G-Eazy discussed in a 2014 interview with HipHopDX:

Mac Dre means everything to Hip-Hop in the Bay. Mac Dre is more than a legend. He just had such a big like catalog of these mixtapes and albums. He had so much music. So it was like, when Mac Dre really, really, really caught on, which was around the time he died unfortunately, that was when everyone really got swept up into it. He was the biggest force in the Bay.

Drake also paid respect to Dre on “The Motto,” which appears later in the Take Care tracklist—in 2016, Dre’s mom told Rolling Stone how these shout-outs inspired her to make a documentary on her son’s life:

I met with Drake in San Francisco and we sat down and he talked with me about how Mac Dre impacted his life and his career, what he’s doing and the big impact that Mac Dre had when Drake was a young boy. So listening to that, it kind of opened up my eyes that maybe I do need to do this. If Andre was alive he would definitely be capitalizing and making as much money as he could.

Whether it be Toronto City Councillors supporting Drake during the beef he had with Meek Mill, or Toronto radio stations playing him more than any other artist, Toronto always gives love back to Drake—just like Bay Area hip-hop fans supported Mac Dre.



Drake with Toronto Politician Norm Kelly, a supporter of Drake during the Meek x Drake beef

I can see why the fuck I disgust you, I must be
 Allergic to failure, ‘cause everytime I come close to it
 I just sneeze, but I just go achoo then a-chieve!
tate_text:
He has an allergic reaction to failure that causes him to sneeze when he comes close to it. Causes him to go Atchoo (At you) and achieve. Thus fulfilling/achieving his aims.

You can now also see why he disgusts you, because his allergy to failure causes him to go ATCHOO AT YOU. You better get a handkerchief.

Since his allergic symptoms consist of sneezing, the pause after the ‘a’ of the a-llergic is him about to sneeze (a…), but then he catches himself in time to finish the verse.

Achieve (here pronounced atchee) is also a sneezing noise.

It is also worthy of notice that the song ends on the same note it started with : “Being ill”. This might be interpreted as having been the fittest to survive in the rap competition thanks to his illness (dope rapping) in an illmatic sense.

tate_text:
Wrong! They would get back together and remarry … only to divorce second time :(

They met as teenagers and were inseparable. As Eminem told Rolling Stone:

We’re talking about a woman who’s been a part of my life since I can remember. She was thirteen when I met her. I was fifteen.

Interestingly, as Em’s grandmother explains, Em’s mother more-or-less adopted Kim at this time and the two were raised as brother and sister. That’s a big part of why they were together all the time as teenagers.

“Dutty” means “dirty” in Jamaican patois.
Originating from Jamaica, “wine” is a form of dance, normally done by women, involving rotation of hips and waist. “Dutty Wine”, in particular, refers to a sexually explicit dance, including movement of legs in a butterfly motion and swinging of head. It is usually danced to the song  “Dutty Wine” by Tony Matterhorn.

The friends used this line to describe the freedom of America in the aformentioned song. This time, they are joking around, because they are at a wedding, and they are saying that they don’t have freedom anymore. They joke that they lost their freedom because of their wives, which is confirmed in the second next line, “Something you will never see again.”

ref_text:
Nothing else ever seems to hurt like the smile on your face
 When it's only in my memory, it don't hit me quite the same
 Maybe it's a cause for concern, but I'm not at ease
 Keeping my head to the curb
tate_text:
Suspecting her man has betrayed her, Beyonce is hurt and suspicious. Going over happy and joyful memories in her mind she can’t decide if her lover has something to hide. Was that last smile genuine or concealing something?

Using a rewording of a common phrase in rap, and one used by Jay Z numerous times —see “Streets Is Talking”—Beyonce says she will be keeping her ear “to the curb” to try to find out what is going on with her lover.

The phrase “I’m not at ease” may refer to the title of a Chinua Achebe novel, No Longer at Ease, about a young British-educated Nigerian man whose family opposes his marriage to the love of his life because of traditional taboos. It is one of many references on LEMONADE and in the accompanying music videos to Nigerian culture and artists.

ref_text:
They say everything happens for a reason
 And people change like the seasons, then grow apart
tate_text:
People are always experiencing and thus oftentimes change in manner and beliefs. Cole compares the extremities of the changes people go through to the radical differences between the seasons. Change in people consequently causes separation and a growing distance. Because ‘'everything happens for a reason’‘, these situations do have a meaning, and are possibly inevitable.

Kanye expressed a similar sentiment in Heard ‘Em Say:

They say people in your life are seasons
And anything that happen is for a reason

ref_text: I'm tired of livin' with demons 'cause they always invitin' more
tate_text:
Negativity breeds negativity

Here Cole admits he has his own demons and they’re always trying to pollute his mental state and get him down.

This could also a Biblical reference. In Luke 11:24-26 (NIV):
“[24] When an impure spirit comes out of a person, it goes through arid places seeking rest and does not find it. Then it says, ‘I will return to the house I left.
[25] When it arrives, it finds the house swept clean and put in order.
[26] Then it goes and takes seven other spirits more wicked than itself, and they go in and live there. And the final condition of that person is worse than the first.”

Cole describes the task of dealing with personal demons, only to bring about new and greater ones. Fame allowed Cole to get out of poverty and support his mother, but now he has deal with the aftermath of it – the distance it has created between him, his family, and his friends.

ref_text: O.J. like, "I'm not black, I'm O.J." …okay
tate_text:
While on trial, O.J. Simpson supposedly uttered the quote “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” Though there’s no substantial evidence, friends and acquaintances back up the theory, and it has been used in media retelling the story since—the earliest being the 2002 documentary O.J.: A Study in Black and White. It also appeared in the 2016 documentary O.J.: Made in America as well as FX’s The People v. O.J. Simpson:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvDMetl7mKU

JAY-Z spoke on this subject in the footnotes special for this song, noting the need for those with visibility to not cast aside their background as a scapegoat:

We tend to, as black people—‘cause we never had anything, which is understandable—we get to a place and we just think we separate ourself from the culture. You know, like where O.J. will get to a space where he’s like, “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” … It’s gonna take for the way-showers to do it and then not get to that point and then turn into like, “I ain’t black, I’m O.J.”

Other sources indicate O.J. may have said the quote during a boycott of the 1968 Olympics, when he was “reportedly pressured by his friend to ‘take a stand’ along with other black Olympic athletes.”

ref_text: Hamilton is out of control
tate_text:
There are actually two ways that this lyric can be taken.

First, Hamilton has no control of himself anymore, letting loose whatever words come out of his mouth. Hamilton denies this, but we have to consider that while Burr is an enemy at this point, Burr still has a relatively level head.

Second, as Madison will make explicit in the next line, it references that Hamilton is out of office again. He has no control of the happenings in the government.

ref_text:
Nigga I can tell you things that you probably shouldn't know
 Have you ever heard the screams when the body hit the floor?
 Flashbacks to the pain, wakin' up, cold sweats
tate_text:
As Cole gets older, he gains knowledge of things that should be kept secret, otherwise they would create issues. Cole goes on to recall a time when someone died, similar to his friend, James, who was killed from gunfire. In “Change,” he says:

Look, somebody laid on the concrete
No time for that, ain’t no lookin' back, ‘cause I’m running too

As a result, flashbacks to the agony (presumably in his sleep) cause Cole to awake with cold sweats, a state where the body becomes moist and cold. Most likely, the suffering stems from the lost of a close friend.

ref_text:
My imagination's too creative
 They see demon, I see angel, angel (Angel), angel
 Without the halo, wingless angel
tate_text:
It’s likely these lines are about her ex-fiancé Pete Davidson. Ariana’s friends and family were relieved that the two broke up. On her August 2018 song, “pete davidson” she sings about an image she created of him in her mind and how she made the relationship come to fruition:

I thought you into my life, woah, look at my mind

Alternatively, this could be about rapper Mac Miller — Grande and Miller dated on-and-off from 2016 to 2018. Their relationship was bogged down, and possibly ruined, by Miller’s battle with substance abuse, which culminated in his fatal September 2018 overdose. Grande touched upon how his addiction affected their relationship on 2018’s “better off,” and admitted via Twitter that the relationship was “toxic.” She also called Miller an angel on “thank u, next”:

Wish I could say thank you to Malcolm
‘Cause he was an angel

ref_text: I buy you Champagne but you love some Henny
tate_text:
Hennessy, or Henny, is a cognac from France. It’s very popular in the African American community and countless rappers have mentioned it in their music (Drake rapped about it in 2015’s “One Dance” and 2012’s “HYFR”). Drake offers champagne, which is a symbol of sophistication and class, but Kiki and KB are more down to earth and from the block, so they prefer Henny.



Drake also goes under the alias of “champagne papi,” as per his Instagram handle. Though he gives her himself (the champagne) she still refuses and prefers something else.

ref_text:
Why you never alone?
 Why you always touching road?
 Used to always stay at home
 Be a good girl, you was in the zone
 Yeah, you should just be yourself
 Right now, you're someone else
tate_text:
“Touch road” is Jamaican slang commonly used in Toronto to mean going out. Drake’s girl seems to be doing this more often than he remembers—he remembers her as a stay-at-home girl who he could get in the zone with whenever they got the chance.

The girl he once knew is gone, and even though he knows it is this new place that has changed her, he has a difficult time accepting that and pleads she should be herself.

ref_text: Death over dishonor
tate_text:
A common saying where a man would rather die than to bring shame or disgrace upon himself.



This was an often repeated theme for 2Pac’s music, including “Troublesome”, “If I Fail”, and “Life of an Outlaw”.





In contrast to the message of glory and honor for a college-educated rapper like J. Cole, “death before dishonor” is also a common expression among United State Marine Corps members and alumni.

ref_text:
Die for what you believe, only one god recedes
 When the shots spray, spray, spray
tate_text:
Death for a higher power is equivalent to death for any cause, maybe for a country, an organization, or a belief: in any case, people are willing to lay their life on the line for abstract concepts. Like the Christian post-hardcore band Thrice said in their song “Like Moths to Flame.”

I nod but don’t know what to say
But I know you
And I believe you’re who you say you are so
I will follow you, lay down my life
I would die for you, this very night

Here, there are two possible meanings.

When Jay says, “Only one God recedes when the shots spray” (bullets fire), he could be referring to himself, the “god in the flesh,” JayHova. He is more pragmatic, rather than idealistic; as the partition in an earlier lyric implies, he keeps a respectful distance from whatever belief system he subscribes to. He isn’t willing to take a bullet for an abstract concept, the archetypal “survivor.”

On the other hands, he might be saying that your god will recede when the shots spray, in your final moments of life. You might reconsider offering up your life to that higher power that was apparently unable to save you when you needed it/Him most.

Another idea is that he’s referring to money. Money is a god to many, and it’s the only god that becomes less important when the shots spray (in the face of death). You can’t take it with you. Belief (knowledge, wisdom, freedom, and understanding) is what you should try to amass before death, and Jay alludes to that in the opening lines of the song.

ref_text:
My expertise checked out in second grade
 When I was 9, on cell, motel, we didn't have nowhere to stay
 At 29, I've done so well, hit cartwheel in my estate
tate_text:
Kendrick was 29 years old when he released DAMN.. At age 9, just after graduating from second grade, Kendrick was living in motels, near Section 8 housing. Back on the bonus song ‘'County Building Blues’' of his 2012 album Good Kid M.a.a.d City he told us about these struggles:

I’ve been waiting on this day since Dr. Dre and Pac
Was on Rosecrans in that burgerstand at ‘95
People staring at 'em in amazement
Reservations at the Days Inn
We was living out a hotel at the time

But 20 years later, he’s ecstatic that his success has allowed him to own property. In 2014, he bought a house is Eastvale, California worth $500,000—a modest price for a wealthy rapper.

Kendrick spoke of his success at the age of 29 on his feature for Isaiah Rashad’s “Wat’s Wrong”:

I told Zay, I’m the best rapper since twenty five
Been like that for a while now, I’m twenty-nine
Any nigga that disagree is a fuckin' liar

ref_text:
Real family stick together and see through the mirage
 The smokescreens, perceptions of false reality
tate_text:
Kanye and Kim have built a family together, one that seems incredibly tight. Being the star of a reality TV show, Kim is constantly in gossip magazines, and “sources” question their relationship on a weekly basis. Cutting through these false statements can be trying, especially when your own family steal from you and blackmail you.

This line could also be foreshadowing a topic discussed later in this song, about how Ye chose to stick with Jay and Tidal instead of following the money with Apple.

The listener should note the delivery of this line: Ye’s voice cracks.  Kanye is showing how his family has helped him overcome his most difficult obstacles and how important that is to him through the tone of voice and pure emotion.

ref_text: You wanted Shady? You got him!
tate_text:
“Slim Shady” is Eminem’s alter ego portrayed by him in his earlier songs. Many critics and listeners to Eminem’s most recent album “Revival” did not like its songs, marking it as “his worst album ever” and demanding the old Slim Shady to be back, hence asking for Eminem to go back to his old style. Em acknowledges and further responds to this in “The Ringer”:

But last week, an ex-fan mailed me a copy
Of The Mathers LP to tell me to study
It’ll help me get back to myself and she’ll love me (ooouuu)
I mailed the bitch back and said if I did that
I’d just be like everyone else in the fucking industry
Especially an effing Recovery clone of me (didn’t I think)

Also, this line goes back to his track “GOAT” in which he states:

You wanted Shady, well, you got it
Man, I ain’t apologizin' for shit

J. Cole’s love songs usually revolve around these two topics:


Being him not being able to obtain the girl he wants, like in “03' Adolescence”, “Power Trip” and “Dreams”.
Him just wanting to have sex like in “Wet Dreamz”.



This is one of the very first songs that he has dove deeper in to the meaning of true love.

He is showing himself as an exposed person, he has fallen in love and he doesn’t care that he is vulnerable; he isn’t trying to “fight it”.

ref_text:
Mix it in a potion like a science
 That liquid G diet got a nigga so quiet
 Cause the shit so strong, got me feeling like I'm dying
 The shit so raw, nothing else can get me higher
tate_text:
Liquid G is a nickname for the drug called “GHB” (gamma hydroxybutyrate), which is a drug generally used in medicine to cure narcolepsy or very rarely alcoholism. It has other nicknames, for example liquid ecstasy, liquid E, liquid X and so on.



Effects include dizziness, drowsiness and slepiness, hence the line

That liquid G diet got a nigga so quiet

Recreational drug users usually use liquid G when the “comedown” of other drugs, such as amphetamines, kick in, to ease the lingering limbo phase. GHB is known to be easy to overdose on, since there’s a small line between the “high” and overdosing.

Cause the shit so strong, got me feeling like I’m dying
The shit so raw, nothing else can get me higher

The Weeknd used to be a heavy drug user,  mentioning his drug addiction in multiple songs, mostly in his early albums, such as the “Trilogy” or “Kiss Land”. He talks about this topic in an interview at The Guardian

ref_text: Whistling
tate_text:
The guitar strum and whistling both come from Paul McCartney’s “Two-Finger Chord & Whistle”. Paul wrote this song after viewing a print of Pablo Picasso’s The Old Guitarist while in the hospital for the birth of his second child, Mary.



After questioning why the guitarist only used two fingers, Paul became inspired to create the song that would eventually be sampled in and interpolated throughout “All Day”.

ref_text:
So I revert to the studio, like hole-in-the-wall diners
 Don't have to be reserved in a booth
tate_text:
Usually, a “hole-in-the-wall” is an easily overlooked place, most commonly a restaurant, that has cheap, low-quality equipment, furniture, etc., but still provides the best food and entertainment on any given night. This could be a reference to the studio where he records his stuff.

Em is playing on the word “reserved"—literally speaking, it’s the matter of not having to hold oneself back, but regarding diners, one doesn’t need a reservation for a table or booth in a place that people have overlooked.

“Booth” is also a reference to a recording booth. Not always a fan of the collateral effects of fame, Em relies on the studio booth as a place where he feels comfortable enough to openly spit whatever comes to his mind.

tate_text:
These lines are reminiscent to bars Kendrick spit on his song, “untitled 05 | 09.21.2014.”:

Watch you when you walk inside your house
You threw your briefcase all on the couch
I plan on creeping through your fuckin' door and blowin' out
Every piece of your brain

“Service” refers to church service. A person’s home and place of worship are considered sacred, but Kendrick would disregard his respect for those structures to enact street justice.

ref_text:
But I'm here for a greater purpose
 I knew right from the start
 I'm just a man of the people, not above but equal
tate_text:
Cole realizes we are all equal; no one person is better or worse than the next. That’s why he continually makes an effort to inspires people to grow as whole; as opposed to people trying to get for a quick dollar.

Curiously enough, on Forbidden Fruit, he says no one is above him “but God himself”, therefore God is the only one who can judge him. Cheeky Cole, also in stark contrast to the rapper he is competeing with and also mentioned in the song, Kanye West. He has a new album and one of his songs is titled “I Am a God”.

ref_text: I ain’t a player, I just ***** * ***
tate_text:
In the original version of this song, the line was:

I’m ain’t a player, I just crush a lot

This line was interpolated from the clean version of Big Pun’s hit song, “Still Not A Player.” The radio friendly version of the song, which substituted the word fuck for crush, included the line “I’m not a player, I just crush a lot.”

https://youtu.be/7Xue-dOOLiY?t=61

Mac references “Still Not A Player” as it also sampled the piano riff from Brenda Russell’s “A Little Bit of Love.”

ref_text:
Everybody gon' say somethin'
 I'd be worried if they said nothin'
tate_text:
While fighting with his girl, it seems that one of them said something they regretted. Kanye’s OK with it, though, since he believes giving your opinion (negative or positive) is better than saying nothing at all.

Kanye has expressed this sentiment before on “Bring Me Down”:

Everybody feel a way about K but at least y'all feel something

And Jay Z said something similar about Ye on The Breakfast Club:

That’s what great art is. It’s polarising… It force you to have an opinion, you know? At least you’re not like wishy washy about it.

ref_text: On your pulse like it's EDM
tate_text:
Rihanna plays on “pulse,” like the human heart beat. EDM (Electronic Dance Music) typically has a BPM (beats per minute) of 125-130.

tate_text:
Hamilton misses the beat here. Burr’s previous lines are all spoken exactly on the drum/snare beat in the background while Hamilton’s line isn’t nearly as syncopated, and is said in between the beat.

This shows Hamilton’s hesitation to duel Burr in the first place, an action reaffirmed by the fact that he throws away his shot during their encounter.

It should also be noted that in the Off Broadway production of this song, Hamilton doesn’t miss the beat in the song, responding to Burr’s challenge almost instantly.

ref_text: I put down the cans and they ran amok
tate_text:
The word “cans” has two meanings here,



First up, Jay took off the headphones (cans). As he says this line, the music stops. Is Jay just taking us back to this “can drop”? If so, the line refers to Jay’s stint with retirement post-Black Album. In that case, “running amok” is a reference to the drop in quality in hip-hop after his “retirement.” If that’s the case, then he calls his headphones “cans” because he compares himself to Picasso, and paints comes in cans.



“Can” is also a slang term for gun, so Jay could be talking about putting down his guns, i.e. retiring from criminal activity. Once he was no longer a gangster, people attempted to exploit his weakness in music.

ref_text: What?
tate_text:
This is the first time Hamilton says “What?” He says this… a lot. Six times in one musical. Some of this can be read at face value: the hot-head Hamilton doesn’t often listen to others, and he’s often incredulous when he does.

It can also be read in the hip-hop sense. MCs in hip-hop use “what” as a way of amping up a song; it’s like saying “I can’t hear you” to get a crowd or rapper to be louder. Hamilton’s energy is relentlessly driving the story forward. He and the ensemble are the only people who say “what?” in this way. The singular exception is Jefferson in The Adams Administration and The Reynolds Pamphlet, which are also two of the only songs where Jefferson, rather than Hamilton, is driving the action forward.

ref_text: But along with celebrity comes about 70 shots to your frame
tate_text:
Jay would reference Big’s classic track more explicitly later in the album, but here he uses it as an aggressive statement.

More Money More Problems. Jay is famous for his subliminal disses, and his ability to remain calm and collected when being attacked from all sides. He only explicitly goes after the big fish.

It’s hard to do when you’ve got nothing to prove
Everybody know you better, you in a lose lose
Cause even when you win, ultimately you lose
Real niggas like, “Why Hov talking to Dude?”

His claim here is that by going at Nas hard on wax in this verse, he is bringing him in to the spotlight. During his Breakfast Club interview Charlemagne remarked that the beef “helped Nas”. Jay is sending a warning though: with great fame comes great danger.

ref_text: Don't mind, all my writings on the wall
tate_text:
On the surface, this could refer to walls written with miscellaneous things. Interestingly enough, this is how cavemen communicated early in human history, presenting a potentially visceral characterization of The Weeknd.

The “writings on the wall” is also idiomatic. As an idiom, Abel is alluding to his warnings to girls not to fall in love with him. His lifestyle is so obvious, or stands out as much as writing would on a wall, but girls still keep falling in love with him.

Tumblr has many pictures of his lyrics written on walls or spray painted places.

ref_text:
Alexander Hamilton
 My name is Alexander Hamilton
tate_text:
Our title character finally makes his grand entrance, with a distinctive establishing theme. Just in case you forget the name of our star or aren’t sufficiently ear-wormed by the melody, this motif reoccurs at numerous points throughout the show (spoken 6 times in this cadence by Hamilton himself, and another 9 times by the ensemble). Lin writes in Hamilton: The Revolution (p. 17) that the cadence came to him immediately and that Hamilton has “an absurdly musical name.”

This entrance is set up by introductions by Hamilton’s various contemporaries. Here’s Lin again, talking about this narrative choice (p. 16):

This [song] was originally written as a Burr monologue, when Hamilton was still a “concept album” in my head. It wasn’t until we realized we were writing a musical that we began to divvy up the monologue among the people who bore witness to Hamilton’s life. This owes a debt to the prologue of Sweeney Todd: All our characters set the stage for our main man’s entrance.

tate_text:
When I’m writing, I’m in the syllable game. I’m connecting 5-6-7-8 syllable phrases where every syllable rhymes. I get heavy into that. When I start rapping something, and I think of more syllables that connect with it, sometimes I want to just keep the scheme going forever.

I’ve done it before in songs, where the syllable scheme of the first verse ends up being the syllable scheme of the second verse, and the third verse — all the way down. I do it because the lines start connecting and making sense. Once I find something and lock in, it comes out pretty quick.

tate_text:
Kayla Duckworth, Kendrick’s sister, voices this line. She also appeared at the end of 2015’s “Black Friday.”

Kendrick uses this line to give his dad a shoutout. When he was a newborn baby on his way home from the hospital, his dad was blasting Big Daddy Kane in the car, and his mother asked him to turn it down. His dad refused and said the loud music is good for him. Kendrick is attributing his skills and success in the music industry to his early exposure.

La palabra “chupa” en esta línea puede ser mal interpretada como “tomar alcohol”, este no es el caso en esta ocasión si tienes en cuenta las otras líneas de este verso.




This line means:

“When she sucks she really gets crazy”

but it can be misinterpreted as

“When she drinks she really gets crazy”

“Chupa” means “suck” but in some countries it’s used as “drinking alcohol”, but if you take into account the nature of the other lines in this verse the first translation is more fitting.

ref_text:
Took me too long for this song, I don't deserve you
 I harassed you out in Paris
 "Please come back to Rome," you make it home
tate_text:
JAY-Z and Beyoncé, who have been together some fifteen years, often find themselves under the lens of the world media, and their relationship has regularly been beset by allegations of trouble and infidelity. This famously came to a head in 2016 when Beyoncé released her album Lemonade, which appeared to contain numerous references to her husbands alleged adultery.

Hov seems to confirm his infidelity here and numerous other times throughout 4:44. In the spirit of reconciliation, he concedes that it has taken him too long to offer his apologies—after all, the album dropped just over a year after Lemonade.

His references to Paris and Rome, both European capitals, underline the hectic, jet-setting lifestyle of a power couple made up of two of the planet’s biggest and most successful musical stars. It’s unlikely he is actually asking Beyoncé to join him in Rome, though. Instead, he may be indicating his longing for the strength he feels when he is happy and has his wife by his side; Rome is the historic centre of the Roman Empire, which seemed limitless in its influence at the height of its power.

ref_text: (Even before we got to ten—)
tate_text:
Philip is not only describing the literal events of the duel, but also recalling his childhood aspirations, now cut short.

His father had high hopes for him right from birth, knowing he would “blow us all away.” By the time the audience first hears from him in “Take a Break,” Philip is nine years old and already surpassing all expectations—even before he reaches the age of ten. He is a precocious, innovative, and hardworking child, accomplished in poetry, French, and piano, and aiming high. Even then, he knew he wanted to be not only “like [his] father,” but even “bolder.”

However, just as his French counting lessons with Eliza always seem to cut off before reaching the number ten, Philip’s great aspirations and enormous potential are cut short, fittingly, with a duel that ends before the count of ten.

ref_text:
And still put hands on you
 Stayin' wound up is how I spend time (Get it?)
tate_text:
Em starts a triple entendre here with “still put hands on you”.


The last thing you’re likely to add to a snowman would be some sticks for arms then some mittens or gloves for hands.
Before, Em makes a reference to beef (ground beef). Now he will “put hands on you"— common slang term for hitting someone—but specifically, he "put[s] hands on you” in the way someone puts their hands on round chuck, when making burgers.
Watches have hands put on the face to tell the time. Hereafter, he starts a larger play on words about time.



“Stayin' wound up is how I spend time” goes with the time reference, and is also a triple entendre.


There are watches that, instead of running off of a battery, have a wind up mechanism.
“Wound up” is a common phrase meaning tense, anxious or fidgety. Em spends his time being wound up, or restless and anxious.
“Spend” is a homophone for “spin”. A watch being wound up is what makes the hands spin. In other words, the mechanism being wound up spins time.

ref_text:
Me with no makeup, you in the bathtub
 Bubbles and bubbly, ooh
tate_text:
“Bubbles” occur in both bubbly, another name for champagne, and in bubble baths. In a December 2018 interview with Billboard, Ariana joked:

I am champagne. You know how people say we’re 60 percent water? I’m 60 percent pink Veuve Clicquot.”

In the same interview, Ariana also described her hit November 2018 single, “thank you, next”:

It’s me and my besties tipsy off champagne — and me with a broken heart — just letting it out and having fun."

Ariana toasts champagne whether it’s a difficult time or a celebration. In a December 2018 Pop Sugar interview, she gave the inspiration for the album that will succeed August 2018’s sweetner:

feminine energy and champagne and music and laughter and crying.

Interestingly, in 2010, three years before her career as a musician began to take off, she recorded a song titled “Pink Champagne,” but it did not make it onto her debut album Yours Truly, although she released the studio version in 2013 and performed it during The Honeymoon Tour in 2015.

Credit cards and the scammers
 Wake up Versace, shit life Desiigner
 Takin' all the stacks, oh
tate_text:
Credit card scams employ third party scanning machines that fit over or fully replace a traditional scanner. The process is sometimes called skimming, and involves the illegal device capturing the credit card information, which is then either printed on to a new card or used for online purchases.

Versace is the name of the fashion company founded by designer Gianni Versace, which is also a play on his rap name Desiigner.

ref_text: Young Money eatin', all you haters do is add salt
tate_text:
“Eating” is slang for being wealthy, usually do to your success, which Lil Wayne’s label Young Money Records has a lot of.

Using the term “eating” to mean both succeeding and literally eating, Wayne makes a pun by saying his haters “add salt” (slang for “hate on”).

Wayne had a similar line on Mystikal’s “Original.”

Is this mic on? (Hey, move this way, this way)
 Hey, Hey! Hey! Turn the mic up, c'mon, c'mon
 Is the mic on or not? I want the mic
 We're bringing up nobody, nobody...
 Nobody but the number one rapper in the world
 He done traveled all over the world
 He came back just to give you some game
 All of the little boys and girls, come up here
 (One two, one two, what's happening, fool?)
 Come right here, this is for you, come on up
 Kendrick Lamar, make some noise, brother
tate_text:
This hype man is Ronald Isley, a member of the Isley Brothers. He was first heard on the intro of the version of “i” that was released on TDE’s SoundCloud page in September 2014, but deleted shortly after the song was released as an official single on iTunes. He also appears on the music video. The intro below was cut from the iTunes version, unfortunately, but it does fit with the message of Kendrick’s album.

We got a young brother that stands for something! / We got a young brother that believes in the all of us! / Brother Kendrick Lamar! He’s not a rapper, he’s a writer, he’s an author! / And if you read between the lines, we’ll learn how to love one another! / But you can’t do that — right on! — I said, you can’t do that without loving yourself first.

These words foreshadow what we find out to be one of the central themes of To Pimp a Butterfly: Kendrick doesn’t want to be portrayed (or perceived) as a rapper or associated with the lifestyle thereof; rather, he wants to set an example by standing up for what he believes in, and give positive energy to all who hear his music.

Additionally, one of the most important phrases in Isley’s lines on this track is, “He done travelled all over the world. He came back to give you some game.” This reveals that Kendrick is apparently back in his hometown, Compton, giving this performance, which gives more importance and meaning to the fight that breaks out in the show and what Kendrick tells the crowd to calm them. Kendrick is doing what he talked about in “Another Nigga,” the poem running through the whole album:

Made me wanna go back to the city and tell the homies what I learned / The word was respect / Just because you wore a different gang colour than mine’s / Doesn’t mean I can’t respect you as a black man

Ayy, if you drivin' 'round in some Dri-Fit
 Ayy, I'ma think that you the type to dry snitch
 Hm, mhm, if I see you pull up with the three stripes
 Ayy, ayy, I'ma fuck around and make you my bitch
tate_text:
In 2016, Kanye parted ways with Nike to work with Adidas who agreed to offer him “full creative reign.” And in 2018, Kanye claims that his Yeezy brand now pulls in more money for Adidas than Jordan’s do for Nike, while this is unconfirmed, Adidas did rake in $2.7 billion more in sales than Nike for the 2017 fiscal year.

Drake was rumored to be collaborating with Adidas at the time of this song’s release. This didn’t sit well with Kanye, since Drake has sang his praises for Nike in songs like “Schemin' Up,” where he says:

I ran the game so long I should be wearing Dri-Fit

Dri-Fit is a fabric popularized by Nike to help enhance an athlete’s performance by blocking moisture. “Dry snitching” is a way of tattling indirectly to seem innocent. It’s considered even sneakier than snitching.

All Drake mentions aside, these lines could also allude to when someone on Kanye’s team repurposed a sketch that artist Tony Spackman made while he was at Nike. When Spackman spoke up, Ye had to fire the designer. Since then, however, Kanye has accused Nike of copying his Yeezy designs.

Finally, this song’s producer Francis and the Lights said this about the last line in the verse:

(Come on!) Sing with me (Sing!), sing for the year (Sing it!)
 Sing for the laughter and sing for the tear (Come on!)
 Sing it with me, it's just for today
 Maybe tomorrow the good Lord will take you away
tate_text:
In a song that deals with the impact of music on the listeners, this chorus, sampled directly from Aerosmith’s iconic 1973 power ballad “Dream On”, deals with its impact on the artists.

Life is short, so even artists like Eminem that are reluctant to embrace their impact on listeners eventually feel the need to “sing for the moment” and create music with real meaning while you still have the chance. Em later turned this concept into an Academy Award-winning single with “Lose Yourself”.

“Hands in the air” is often times referenced in a “stick-up” or robbery. After the first verse, it’s Cole’s friend who is being robbed for his watch, being told to put his hands in the air.  Following the second verse however, the tables turn and it’s Cole and his friends performing a stick-up.



2.“Hands in the air” as in getting hype from the music, of course..

as




“Hands in the air” as a surrendering plead to the Lord.  From the context of the song we realize the troubles of sticking around in the “hood”; you either become the victim or the one committing crimes. ref_text:
You walkin' around like you invincible
 You dropped outta school, you lost your principles
 I know people backstab you, I felt bad too
 But this 'fuck everybody' attitude ain't natural
 But you ain't a saint, this ain't kumbaye
tate_text:
Although JAY-Z is still rapping about himself, these lines establish that he’s also beginning to address Kanye West. “You dropped outta school” references Kanye’s 2004 album The College Dropout. There’s also a play on words with “principles” and “principals”—dropping out of school might show a lack of principles, and you would literally no longer have a principal.

“Saint Pablo” is a song that appeared on Kanye’s 2016 album The Life of Pablo and “Saint” is also his son’s first name.

“‘Ye” is an abbreviated version of Kanye’s name, which Jay fuses with “Kumbaya,” the title of a classic campfire spiritual recorded in the 1920s. It’s meant to inspire peace and merriment, which clearly doesn’t fall in line with a “fuck everybody” attitude.

ref_text: There are so many to deflower!
tate_text:
We all know what Burr has on his mind…



In 1860, an anonymous author actually published a sexually explicit biography of Aaron Burr—The Amorous Adventures of Aaron Burr. The book, though undoubtedly highly fictionalized, details a number of his alleged sexual conquests.

This would be fine if Burr, like Drake, lived in the modern world, where he would be free to please as many ladies as would have him. However, by 18th century standards, there’s a bit more going on here.

When Burr is talking about deflowering, he’s literally talking about taking away a woman’s virginity. While pre-marital sex was not exactly verboten in the 18th century—about one-third of colonial brides were pregnant on their wedding days—a lady was expected to marry the man who got her in the family way. If a woman’s chastity was lost, whether it was through a consensual act or rape, her reputation could be ruined.

As women weren’t easily able to retain property or businesses, most had to rely on their husbands or, more tentatively, their fathers and brothers to provide for her income. Thus, if a young woman lost her reputation and became unable make an advantageous marriage, her whole livelihood could be threatened. The higher the class, the more important it was that a woman’s chastity was preserved, as such a girl would not have been brought up to make any contingency plans for her future.

Basically, Burr and his crew can joke all they want, but for women, the act of courtship was a deadly serious business.

ref_text:
See, I've been on a quest for the next wave
 But never mind, that was just a segue
tate_text:
Cole claims that he’s always scoping out new trends in hip hop as if he were on a quest, and that he will pay attention to find this “new wave.” However, he cleverly says that statement was simply using that line to switch up which vowels were rhyming.

Cole also uses wordplay on the term, “segue” which is defined as “move without interruption from one song, melody, or scene to another.” Its homonym, Segway is a two-wheeled motorized vehicle produced by the company of the same name. Cole uses this homonym to describe how Segways were supposed to be the new wave of transportation, but similar to new-age rappers, they quickly “died out”.

ref_text: ‘Cause I just shitted on the mic and I like gettin' cut
tate_text:
The previous bars double the entendre on “bow” (the show bowing/bowing from pain), whereas this bar triples it by adding the “shitting” theme, as bow could be heard as bowel (bowel movement).

The meaning to the extended metaphor pretty much lies in this statement :

Him giving up on the game (bowing out), would be as crazy as him stabbing himself in the gut (bow from pain) while wiping his butt (bowel movement)…wiping his butt because he just shitted on, got MAD DOPE on the mic. Why would he give up when he’s the best at it.

ref_text: Awesome. Wow
tate_text:
George insultingly utilizes the American accent. He also uses words that commonly are used by sarcastic teenagers who most pointedly DO NOT think whatever they are talking about is awesome.

It’s a fun anachronism, too, since during this period, the standard English and American accents were largely the same—in fact, they were both closer to the American accent we hear today. The British accent as we know it now (called “Received Pronunciation”) disseminated largely in the 19th century. So George’s “Awesome, wow”—for all its mocking, Valley Girl sensibility—is actually be closer to his true accent at the time.

ref_text: And it’s quiet uptown
tate_text:
At the time, settlement in Manhattan was still so concentrated to the south of the island of that city maps of the era only bothered to show downtown.

Living on an estate of over thirty acres nine miles to the north provided the Hamilton family with seclusion and peace far from the noise and bustle of the city.

When Hamilton arrives in New York, he thrives on the city’s surging energy—reflected in the vigorous movements of the ensemble around him in “Alexander Hamilton”—as it matches the churning of his own ambitions.

But now, in the midst of his grief, the quiet of uptown (and the restraint of the staging of this song) matches the emptiness of his family’s loss.

ref_text:
Hi, my name is, what? My name is, who?
 My name is, chka-chka, Slim Shady
 Hi, my name is, huh? My name is, what?
 My name is, chka-chka, Slim Shady
tate_text:
Dre put on the Labi Siffre record, and I was just like “Hi! My name is!” That beat was talking to me. I was like, “Yo, this is it, this is my shot. If I don’t impress this guy, I’m going back home and I’m fucked.” I knew Dre wasn’t an easy person to please. I made sure that everything he had a beat for, I had a rhyme ready to go, or I came up with a rhyme on the spot.

“My Name Is” was the first thing that came out of my mouth that first day I was at Dre’s house. I don’t know if we released what I did the first day or if I re-did it, but it was basically the same. I didn’t understand punching, or believe in it. So I would just go from the top of the song all the way down. I was never flying in hooks. Everything was live, one take. If I got all the way to the fucking end, and messed up the last word, I’d be like “Run it back, let’s do it again.” I remember Dre was like “Yo, are you fucking crazy? Let’s just punch.” I didn’t like that concept because I wasn’t used to it. When we were recording here in Detroit, in the beginning, I was saving up my money to go in. We only had an hour, you know? I’m like “One take down, alright, let’s go to the next song. Fuck it.” That’s what I was used to.

You got people you love you sold drugs to

tate_text:
JAY-Z rapped about the guilt he felt selling drugs on his 1997 song “You Must Love Me”:

All you did was motivate me
“Don’t let ‘em hold you back”
What I do? I turned around and I sold you crack
I was a bastard for that, still I’m drowning in shame

While many listeners thought the lyric was about Jay’s mother, Gloria, he told VIBE Magazine:

When I said that, I meant [it as] a metaphor for, like, the mothers of our nation.

On 2013’s “Holy Grail,” Jay also rapped about how addictive fame can be—like boosting his ego and feeling invincible, as if he were on drugs.

ref_text:
Monsieur Hamilton
 
 
 Monsieur Lafayette
tate_text:
Since Lafayette is from France, he would naturally call Hamilton “Monsieur.” This is the French equivalent of “Mister,” with a respectful connotation of “sir.”

The line is said in a bit of a mocking tone, as Lafayette is gently teasing his friend about his recent rise in station. Hamilton archly responds in kind, because he is a gentleman!

Hilariously, they’re both addressing each other wrong. Hamilton should rightfully be “Lt. Col. Hamilton” and Lafayette should of course be Marquis de Lafayette. Lafayette wasn’t even his actual last name, just his title! By English naming standards, he’d need to be Monsieur du Motier! In the French, he’d more rightfully be Monsieur le Marquis de Lafayette, or just Monsieur le Marquis. Aristocrats! What can you do?

As in “Farmer Refuted,” “The Room Where It Happens,” and “Your Obedient Servant,” these little moments of sarcasm provide some levity for the audience in the play’s calm-before-the-storm moments (“Farmer Refuted” quickly turns violent after Hamilton mocks Seabury, a ferocious battle starts after Hamilton and Lafayette end their conversation, the hectic compromise emerges after Hamilton and Burr’s friendly conversation in “The Room Where it Happens,” and we all know what happens after “Your Obedient Servant”).

ref_text:
See, I invented Kanye, it wasn't any Kanyes
 And now I look and look around and there's so many Kanyes
tate_text:
Kanye flexes his influence on music, fashion, and popular culture.

The vast majority of popular rappers today—Drake, Childish Gambino, Big Sean, J. Cole, Kendrick Lamar, Chance The Rapper, Tyler, The Creator, A$AP Rocky, Travis Scott—have all been influenced by Kanye one way or another. He also credits himself and Don C. with bringing back the Jordan Retro’s. In a 2013 interview with Sway Calloway, Kanye said:

The Jordans are only popular at this point because of two people — me and Don C. Because Don C was ordering them vintage Jordans when the IVs used to break apart at the sole. We were wearing them with the Louis Vuitton backpacks with the Polos. Brand Jordan looked at us and said, ‘Oh man, we’ve got to start retroing them.’

According to How Many of Me, there are only 1,610 “Kanye’s” in the United States and only one of them has the surname “West.” Were the other 1,609 named after the Kanye West?

ref_text:
OG one, told me one, show me one, eight ways
 How to segue
tate_text:
Section.80, good kid, m.A.A.d. city, and To Pimp A Butterfly all feature tracks that “segue” into one another, or blend cohesively.

It’s likely the “OG” Kendrick mentions is his mentor Dr. Dre, who signed Kendrick to Aftermath Entertainment in 2011. After meeting Dre, his next two albums—good kid, m.A.A.d. city and To Pimp A Butterfly—featured increased thematic cohesion compared to Section.80.

tate_text:
This introduction follows the same template as those of “A Winter’s Ball”, “Guns and Ships” and “Your Obedient Servant”, as well as “Alexander Hamilton” and “What’d I Miss?” at the opening of each act.

These passages, all delivered by Burr with a tone of pointed incredulity, effectively function as a dramatic prologue to different sections of the musical. Here, Burr’s narration continues through the entire song, essentially giving a relatively concise summary of the political situation so that the action thereafter can focus on Hamilton himself.

ref_text:
Four in the mornin', and I'm zonin'
 I think I'm possessed, it's an omen
tate_text:
See above

 The book “Skinhead” by Nick Knight (the video’s director) might be a good start. Skinhead has its roots in the British Mod subculture.The music that Mods listened to was primarily Jamaican Ska and Northern Soul (Motown). It was mostly being played by black DJ in London clubs. The skinhead look is a British working class interpretation of the Jamaican Rude Boy look. I think that Kanye is aware of this history. I think in a way he is calling for unity among the oppressed (aka poor) regardless of color.

ref_text: Slaughter
tate_text:
Burr’s use of this word is interesting, as Merriam-Webster defines slaughter as:

1 :  the act of killing; specifically :  the butchering of livestock for market
2 :  killing of great numbers of human beings (as in battle or a massacre) :  carnage"

This might imply that Hamilton’s death was, in Burr’s opinion, wrong, and a crime (despite how he was portrayed in court after the duel).

Based on his statement that Hamilton would take “deadly aim,” Burr likely expects that the duel will end in his own death.

ref_text:
Girl, why can't you wait? (why can't you wait, baby?)
 Girl, why can't you wait 'til I fall out of love?
tate_text:
Abel could be referring to his breakup with Selena Gomez: shortly after they broke up, she started dating her ex, Justin Bieber; not giving Abel enough time to get over the relationship.

On the other hand, Abel was spotted leaving Bella Hadid’s apartment–who he dated previous to Gomez–shortly after, indicating that maybe he didn’t need much time after all.

These lines also call back to Thursday, where he sings on “The Birds (Part 2)”:

She said please, mercy me, mercy me
Let me fall outta love, before you fuck her

The Birds (Part 2) by was released roughly 6 years before this song. Back then, the Weeknd would  describe himself as somewhat emotionless and would disregard the slightest chances of having a serious relationship. He’d hint that women would be foolish to fall in love with him due to these personality traits. When used in comparison with the current track, a significant change in Abel’s life and his ways is depicted.

The tables have definitely turned since his Thursday mix-tape, in the most ironic of ways. He now finds himself in love with someone, begging her not to leave. He asks her to stay a little longer in order to ease the pain of her future departure, much as the woman on The Birds (Part 2) asked him years ago.

As painful as this may be for him, it does portray his emotional growth in relation to woman. He allowed himself to care for someone enough to get hurt.

ref_text: Coming up, coming down
tate_text:
When considering the hook, (I don’t pop molly..) this could be an allusion to the effects of molly; the come up being when the high is building and the come down being when the person is sobering up

But, as Hov explained in the album’s promo videos, a major theme here is the dichotomy of success: the more you have, the more you have to lose, etc. This line is a slight nod to the up’s & down’s of life. It’s something Jay has played around with before,

Same sword they knight you they gon' good night you with
Sh.., Thats' only half if they like you
That ain’t even the half what they might do
Don’t believe me, ask Michael
See Martin, see Malcolm
You see Biggie, see Pac, see success and its outcome
See Jesus, see Judas; see Caesar, see Brutus
See success is like suicide

However, he goes into greater depth on this album, and seems to have a more positive outlook on success at this point.

ref_text: Why you kicking that soda can?
tate_text:
“Kicking a can down the road” is an idiom which means to procrastinate or to consistently ignore a problem or issue. The cop may not recognize that there is an issue, which is why he asks this question.

Kicking a can also refers to a children’s game dating back to the 1930s that was popular in poor neighborhoods. A racist white police officer might ask this question simply because he doesn’t understand the culture in which games like these originate, whether it’s repurposing a soda can or a record player.

ref_text: Just remember, what happens on Earth stays on Earth!
tate_text:
Kid Capri also dropped this line on “ELEMENT.”  It’s an adaption of the phrase “what happens in Vegas, stays in Vegas,” but also alludes to the Bible verse 1 Timothy 6:7:

For we brought nothing into this world, and it is certain we can carry nothing out.

Kid Capri also annotated this line on “ELEMENT.,” saying:

To tell the truth, I never asked Kendrick the meaning of it. I said what I said and I never asked him the meaning. He told me to say that part.

The most interesting detail about this line is that Kendrick considered titling the album “What Happens on Earth Stays on Earth,” as stated in an interview with Big Boy.

ref_text: Body smoking, so they call me Young Nicki Chimney
tate_text:
Nicki’s body is “smoking”, which is slang for hot or attractive. Because of this, people call her a “chimney” because chimneys release smoke.

Even though Nicki is figuratively smoking, she needs a literal chimney to release all the smoke caused by her hotness!

This isn’t her first time making a chimney pun—she did so here in Young Money’s “Finale” also.

ref_text:
Do I do it for the love of the music or is there more to me?
 Do I want these niggas to worship me?
 False prophets
tate_text:
Following the previous lines regarding intentions, Cole takes a moment to reflect on his own. In Cole’s view, the love of music should be the main motivating factor for himself and his fellow rappers, as opposed to chasing success, riches, fame, or adulation. Those who do that and want others to worship them for it are false prophets.

While speaking with Microphone Check, Cole explained that although he has faith in the things that he speaks on, he doesn’t feel equipped to speak for others and be their “prophet.”

I’ve believed deeply in the things that I believe in and like, if you know me you know I’m passionate about these things I’m talking about everyday, but at the same time […] I don’t feel like the best candidate to be the voice of the generation.

ref_text: And actually comin' from humble beginnings
tate_text:
Em had a challenging childhood, being raised by his single mother, after his father abandoned the household when he was a baby. His mother, Debbie, struggled to keep a job, which resulted in the two constantly moving around.

He was bullied by neighbourhood kids, and class mates, due to him constantly being the “new kid”, and because he stood out in predominantly African American areas. His mother was addicted to prescription pills, leaving Em to care for himself. He has detailed his childhood on songs such as “My Mom, “Cleanin Out My Closet”, and “Headlights.”

ref_text: Steering clear of any headaches to start
tate_text:
Ariana avoids certain subjects or situations that could cause conflict i.e. headaches, between her and her partner. She finds herself walking on eggshells and not being completely truthful, in order to avoid angering her significant other.

Alternatively, this may be a reference to Ariana’s stance post-relationship. She wants to make it clear that she is in no place for a boyfriend or any commitment – as referred to later in the song she is better off being free. She is looking to avoid any drama or stress that a toxic relationship may bring. Even if she pursues a physical relationship, she makes her intentions clear at the beginning, so that no “headaches” come if the other person happens to get attached.

Moving on from trauma and headaches is a theme throughout Sweetener with songs like “no tears left to cry”. It is also the subject of the first release of her following album, thank u next, with the titular track “thank u next” expressing her intention to move on from the past.

ref_text: 'Cause everything's commercial and it's pop now
tate_text:
Considering the lyrics above about Cole listening to party rap in 2003, he’s likely saying this in a knowingly ironic way.

The “bunch of folks” have been complaining about Hip-Hop being commercialized since the days that J. Cole was 18 and listening to music about money, pussy, and parties. And even before then.

Perhaps most famously in Common’s 1994 classic “I Used To Love H.E.R.”

The first commercialized rap record was released by Sugarhill Gang in 1979, and in 1981, the Hip-Pop song “Rapture” by Blondie went #1, appropriating Hip-Hop almost immediately.

ref_text: I said I didn't feel nothing, baby, but I lied
tate_text:
Abel is notorious for his sexual escapades. He has not only spoken about his sexual prowess but also how detached he is in sexual situations and relationships. This physical-emotional detachment has been a constant theme in his music since his first mixtape, House of Balloons, and essentially facilitated the underlying plot of his second mixtape Thursday. This is almost as consistent and ever-present as allusions to his myriad drug-fueled adventures.

However in “Adaptation” he demonstrates a self-awareness and desire for a meaningful feeling involved relationship:

Then I realized
She might have been the one
I let it go
For a little fun

So while he likely warned her that he was trouble along the lines of his famous line from “The Zone”:

I can’t feel a damn thing

At his core, Abel does have a capacity to love. So despite saying he didn’t harbor any real feelings towards her, as he admits, he lied.

This isn’t the first time Abel has boasted about lying either, on “Montreal” he boasts how it comes natural to him,

Cuz ain’t nobody feels the way that I feel when I’m alone
So if I said that I won’t call
The lying comes natural to me

ref_text: Alien brain, you Satanist (Yeah)
tate_text:
Eminem declared himself an alien on January 2018’s “Chloraseptic (Remix)”:

It’s ‘cause I’m an alien, that’s why I write 'til the page is outta space

He calls MGK a Satanist since he named his diss track, “Rap Devil.” The title of the diss track is a play on one of Em’s most popular hits, “Rap God.” The devil, or Satan, is considered to be the antithesis of God.

This line also connects with “In vain” in the previous line, a religious phrase found in The Ten Commandments:

Thou shalt not take the name of the LORD thy God in vain; for the LORD will not hold him guiltless that taketh his name in vain.

Being the highest selling artist of the ‘00s, Eminem has played to many sold out stadium shows.

Upon his curtain call (following his encore,) Eminem’s fans toss flowers onto the stage, which is a traditional way of visually thanking “an artist for a superb performance.” While this imagery is a nod to the covers of Encore and Curtain Call (which were taken during the same shoot,) this lyric also acknowledges Eminem’s uncertainty as to whether this would be his last album and/or original song, which would make this the final bow of his career.

Abel exposed his lifestyle through his trilogy of mixtapes and let us be part of all the occurrences that took place within that period of his life. Before dropping House of Balloons, people didn’t even knew about The Weeknd and throughout 2011, his fans were desperate to find every piece of information they could get to know more about him.

Now that The Weeknd is a well-known artist, he has nowhere to hide. He used to be untraceable and now is on every single social media. Abel feels that this 180-degree change in his life has put him in a delicate position, where he doesn’t feel comfortable.

He regrets opening up to their fans stating that it’s just wrong that they know so much about him when that wasn’t his intention in the first place given that the main attraction to The Weeknd was his mystery.

ref_text: In the land of the killers a sinner's mind is a sanctum
tate_text:
Eminem admits that he is far from perfect. He raps about rape and violence, and has a long list of legal troubles. But despite all that, he has never been affiliated with a gang or participated in gun violence. So in a genre that is becoming more and more influenced by the gang-banging lifestyle, Eminem claims that his music is actually becoming the lesser of two evils. Normally the mind of a sinner would be thought of as a dark and dangerous place, but compared to the mind of a murderer it’s preferable.



Similar idea to the phrase “in the land of the blind the one-eyed man is king”. In other words, having one eye isn’t ideal, but when surrounded by a bunch of blind people you are going to be thankful for what you have.

Kanye announced on Twitter that this verse would give Hot 97 radio host Ebro Darden closure over their interactions regarding Kanye’s support for right-wing “free thinkers” Donald Trump and Candace Owens.

https://twitter.com/kanyewest/status/989916597195173888

While it’s not fully clear whether Kanye was intentionally making a statement to Ebro, just trolling, or insinuating that he had been trolling the entire time, this verse ended up going viral, sparking memes, reaction videos, and even a trollish J. Cole-mentioning remix by Smokepurpp.

Alternately, he may be talking about God. Even though God is not always present in every decision and moment in our lives, he’s always right where we need him to be. By not being there he helps us learn from our mistakes, and by being there he prevents us from going down the wrong path.

Another reference is he could also be reaching out to his fans, saying that they were always where he needed them to be, whether backing him up from the get go or discovering him after he made his come up.

ref_text: Then defend it
tate_text:
Combined with Hamilton’s line above, Miranda seems to be alluding to the oath of office for the United States Senate:

“I, AB, do solemnly swear (or affirm) that I will support and defend the Constitution of the United States against all enemies, foreign and domestic; that I will bear true faith and allegiance to the same; that I take this obligation freely, without any mental reservation or purpose of evasion, and that I will well and faithfully discharge the duties of the office on which I am about to enter. So help me God.”

Perhaps foreshadowing Burr’s election to the Senate, or just Hamilton poking fun at Burr for his obvious political ambitions?

However, if this is an allusion to the above oath, it is an anachronism. The original oath of office for the Senate, enacted in 1789 by the First Congress, simply read, “I, A.B. do solemnly swear or affirm (as the case may be) that I will support the Constitution of the United States.” It wasn’t until after the Civil War that oaths were made more specific, for obvious reasons. The longer oath quoted above wasn’t enacted until 1884, with a minor change in 1966.

You can read a more detailed history here.

ref_text:
And I, I just can't pretend
 Seen too much, it's so hard for me to let new people in
tate_text:
A Jewish mother in a comfortable Toronto suburb. A black father in Memphis. A successful career as a TV actor, and a world famous rapper. Drake’s seen a lot.

He repeats this sentiment on the outro for this project, saying he’s seen it all.

He’s actually been saying this for years:

I’ve seen a lot, man. I’ve seen a lot of life, put it that way. I’ve been with the most blessed kids in the world. I’ve been with people whose life is right at the bottom of the barrel. I was on a TV show, I went to art school, I went to hood schools. I’ve lived. I’ve lived a full 24 years, man.

ref_text: Who your real friends? We all came from the bottom
tate_text:
Kanye channels Drake’s monster hit “Started From The Bottom”:

Fuck a fake friend, where your real friends at?

His slow rise to the top is documented in “Last Call”, a track that blatantly calls out people who believed in him from the very beginning of his career, when he was just making beats and trying to convince people he could rap.

Despite his current fashion industry connections, Kanye is shouting out his day one hip hop family, transitioning between his attempts to integrate in to fashion with his already ingrained status in music.

Trying to follow him around and just praising him.  He wants to be normal and not always be followed or always surround by security and hang arounds. He doesn’t need all his cling ons and yes men in the studio trying to pamper him and do everything for him. The reference to them wiping his ass not only implies that they are even willing to do the nasty work just to appease Eminem but that they’re slowly trying to clean up his act and he doesn’t need no one to clean up his act

“Wipe my ass” is also referring to the last line when he said “point me to the closest restroom”

ref_text:
I'll be feelin' pain, I'll be feelin' pain just to hold on
 And I don't feel the same, I'm so numb
 I'll be feelin' pain, I'll be feelin' pain just to hold on
 And I don't feel the same, I'm so numb
tate_text:
Pain in this case isn’t necessarily physical, but mental. X is describing what it feels like to go through depression.

When depressed, many people feel that it takes a lot of energy just to be happy. It’s strenuous to keep yourself from breaking down and giving into your depressive thoughts.

Simultaneously, a lot of emotions are forgone and replaced by this feeling of eternal sadness. The weight of the world sits on your shoulders and makes you numb to a lot of feelings.

X describes not only the mental agony of depression, but also likely self harm, which he mentions in other songs and which many speculate he has a history of. Many (though not all) people who self harm do it because they feel emotionally and/or physically numb, and physical pain creates a tangible distraction from the mental anguish of depression; it allows people to feel something, to have some groundedness in reality, to hold on.

ref_text: Father—
tate_text: Note the change from the more informal “Pops” to the more somber and polite “Father,” as the conversation becomes more serious. Philip is taken aback by Hamilton’s lack of enthusiasm, more adult perspective, and implicit disapproval regarding the duel. He clearly expected this exchange to go very differently, especially considering that he entered the duel to protect his father’s reputation.

ref_text: I flip my misfortune and grow me a fortune
tate_text:
The “misfortune” he refers to is likely the impoverished circumstances in which he was raised, as he spent part of his childhood living in a Fayetteville trailer park.  Cole discusses such an upbringing in his 2014 interview with Music Times:

There were days when my mom would have to scrape up nickels and dimes to give me $1.50 lunch money,“ Cole said. "And I would know she wasn’t eating lunch that day so that I could.

He transformed or, “flipped” such misfortune into a fortune, as his impoverished upbringing provided him with material for his music, but it also instilled in him a hunger to overcome the odds and make it in the rap game. While Cole never actually sold drugs himself, they were all around him growing up, hence the album’s drug and addiction theme. So it’s possible the “misfortune” he refers to is not just about being broke, but about about growing up around drugs and dealers, specifically. From this perspective, “flip” refers to the buying and reselling of drugs for profit. This is actually the 2nd time on this album that he’s rapped about flipping drugs, with the first being on the track, “KOD” where he raps:

This is what you call a flip
Ten keys from a quarter brick
Bentley from his mama’s whip

ref_text:
Don't call it a comeback
 It was dark, now the sun back
 Hit me hard, but I punched back
tate_text:
Weezy felt like a prisoner to Birdman and Cash Money Records when they refused to let him release Tha Carter V back in 2014:

https://twitter.com/LilTunechi/status/540569858287493120?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E540569858287493120&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.complex.com%2Fmusic%2Flil-wayne-cash-money-beef-timeline%2F

2014 to 2018 was a dark time for Wayne, since he did not want Birdman and Cash Money to profit off his work, so he refused to release music in a traditional manner. He sued Birdman and ended up settling in June 2018. After a long battle, Weezy is a free artist, shining again on the rap game.

“Don’t call it a comeback” is a legendary line in hip-hop history, dating back to LL Cool J’s 1991 hit “Mama Said Knock You Out”:

Don’t call it a comeback, I been here for years

ref_text:
Said angel, woah oh oh oh
 You'll probably never take me back and I know this
 Yeah I know this, aw man
 I said angel, woah oh oh oh
 I'm so desensitized to feeling these emotions
 Yeah, no emotions baby
tate_text:
These lines parallel well to the ending of the Kiss Land narrative expressed through “Tears in the Rain,” where The Weeknd places himself in the position of the wrong-doer and the girl as the victim.

Listeners typically hear The Weeknd paint images of himself as the devilish leader that brings the women he interacts with down. Sometimes, we see these women represented as weak and easily susceptible to sin, but in cases such as here, we see the women empowered, painted as pure and above The Weeknd.

The Weeknd, knowledgeable of his sins and mistakes, has destroyed any emotions and cares that could help repair his disconnect with these angels. This leads to the repetition of the narrative.

As with much of the album, the romantic relationship can sometimes be interpreted as a metaphor for his rise to fame and change in lifestyle/image. He hopes his original fans will still relate to and love him after this change, but he fears they won’t take him back.



There are also strong parallels to “Adaptation,” with Abel acknowledging that he has traded love for a life of drugs, sex, and fame.

ref_text: I see the guilt beneath the shame
tate_text:
He feels guilty for the mistakes he has made, or maybe he feels shameful for some of the things he’s done and that he thought were “okay”–but in reality he actually does feel guilty for what he’s done to others.

This could also be a reference to his drug habit–he thought a little bit of illegal substance didn’t “hurt”–but in reality, there is severe guilt in the aftermath.

ref_text:
Chuck the deuces, chugging D'USSÉ, ugh
 Fuck what you say, boys in blue say
tate_text:
To “chuck the deuces” means to throw up the peace sign.



Further enhancing their laid-back nature is the addition of the cognac D'USSÉ , a brand that Jay heavily endorses, featuring references on “Drunk In Love”, the sister to this song.

It’s a very hippie attitude. Jay’s dislike for the boys in blue (police) is well known, and he compares their relentless pursuit of him to that of gossip sites and paparazzi, with their rumour-mongering.

Peace. They don’t care.

tate_text:

Deep stuff Wayne

ref_text: You don't know what the fuck I've been through
tate_text:
Given that 8 Mile was largely based on Eminem’s life, his character Jimmy/B-Rabbit and him share many of the same struggles that Eminem actually faced while growing up in Detroit.
In the movie, B-Rabbit’s mom is a broke alcoholic who lives in a trailer with an abusive boyfriend and her daughter. Just as Eminem is protective of his daughter Hailie, Jimmy is protective of his little sister, which leads to several arguments with his mom regarding her irresponsibility as a parent.
In addition to trying to escape a broken home and poverty, Jimmy struggles greatly as a white artist trying to succeed in a predominantly black art form, reflecting Eminem’s own problems with being booed off stage during similar rap battles. With all of this pent-up rage and suffering, Jimmy angrily lashes out at Papa Doc, claiming someone as entitled as him (as Jimmy explains following these lines) could never understand the pressure and problems that Jimmy faces.

tate_text:
The A&R men (Artists and Repertoire) are middlemen between the record label and the artists. They oversee talent scouting, album production, etc.

Many record labels can be very controlling about what they want an artist to sound like, but this is rarely the case for a well-established rapper like Drizzy.

They’re happy that they could just go in the studio and do their thing without being told what to do.
