tate_text:
Kendrick pours detail into his encounter with the homeless man throughout the majority of the second verse, leading into a climactic final verse.



The homeless man’s empty stare pierces Kendrick. He becomes intrigued and doesn’t leave. As Kendrick becomes angry at the man, he articulates emotions of disrespect, anger, confusion – comparing his anger to throwing a baseball bat at the man’s throat.

This narrative paints a metaphor that calls to mind biblical parables, such as the story of Cain and Abel (“Am I my brother’s keeper?”) and
Matthew 25:45:

Truly I tell you, whatever you did not do for one of the least of these, you did not do for me.

“Like I was supposed to save him” can also be seen as foreshadowing the true identity of the man—the dramatic irony is excruciating.

By leaning away as Hamilton walks determinedly forward, the company is anticipating the promise, almost threat in Hamilton’s words: just you wait until you see what I’m going to do. This choreography lends visual support to what we’re learning about Hamilton—he’s a force of nature, and he’s going to try to bend everyone around him to his will.

ref_text: So quick-witted
tate_text:
It is at this point that Jefferson abandons any pretense of advocating for a political cause. He is no longer concerned with delivering creative rhymes or any sort of thought-out response. He devolves into vague insults that require the audience to fill in the blanks.

For example, he intones this line with bitter sarcasm, but he does not bother to explain why Hamilton’s quick wit has provoked Jefferson’s nearly audible eye-rolling. Perhaps he finds Hamilton’s latest remarks to be, in truth, foolish; he may be highlighting Hamilton’s remarkable ability to improvise excuses for moral failings; he could be jealous; or – since Hamilton’s had Washington’s favor all along – Hamilton’s metaphorical preening is needless, morally grotesque, and purely autoerotic in nature.

Jefferson could be implying a great many things, but the consistent message is that it does not truly matter which implication is intentional because nearly everyone in the room dislikes Hamilton. They are more than happy to decide for themselves why Hamilton’s rapid-fire retorts are so repugnant. Hamilton will find himself friendless and powerless someday, and his own formidable brain will be the architect of his downfall.

Ultimately, this line summons the concept of hedonism, and it isn’t the first time The Weeknd has done so. Although the girl may suffer knowing that her time with Abel is severely limited, she’s going to ensure that she maximizes the amount of pleasure and content she leaves with when it’s all over.

tate_text:
If one is to “go behind your back”, well then that person is saying negative things about you while you aren’t there to defend yourself. Usually when someone does this, they are completely nice to you while you share one-another’s company. When one does this, they are considered two-faced.
Nun-chucks (also know as Nunchaku) are a weapon that consist of two sticks and are connected by a rope or chain.





In this line Wayne could either be referring to:


Someone specific who has friends who speak negatively about them when they aren’t around
Or people who go behind someone’s back are considered “bitch niggas”.



#Regardless
Wayne made a clever comparison of people placing nun-chucks behind their back

tate_text:
By breaking his step-father’s nose, this kid simultaneously destroyed the order his parents had worked so hard to uphold. Their kid is no longer obedient, and is going as far as to punch his step-dad in the face in rebellion. The parents have no control over their child, and the child has no control over his actions.



The fact that the kid says this “house” is a broken home implies that he never really felt at home there in the first place. It was just the place where he spent his time without ever fitting in.

ref_text: You keep me in your orbit
tate_text:
In astronomy, an orbit refers to a circular path followed around a celestial body. For example, the Earth is known to orbit around the sun.



Mac was a central figure in Ariana’s life, and her life in many ways revolved around him.

Scientifically, the earth orbits the Sun due to the gravitational pull of the sun. Similarly, Ariana is inexplicably drawn to Mac – and can’t simply let go of him – even if he hurts her. Interestingly, lighter objects will always orbit heavier ones which is telling in this tale of toxic relationships. Mac’s struggle with drugs and alcohol may have placed a heavy burden on him, with Ariana hoping to be a light source, lifting some of that weight.

In the interview below with Cole explains that he had some pretty dark thoughts while writing this album, and even suffered from depression from the pressure he faced.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kSzPG0xMpLM&feature=youtu.be

He’s worried that Born Sinner will flop and maybe end his career.

He’s suggesting that part of the reason he’s worried is because he’s letting the Devil in him work, instead of trusting God.

On his Truly Yours 2 EP, Cole hints at the possibility of his album flopping with this line:

But I finally put my Momma in that E class, nigga
And I told her quit her job, but hold your horses
If my next album flops it’s back to the post office, both of us, shit
They’re saying that’s a real possibility
The thought alone is killing me

These lines are also a great play off the previous verse, where he’s asking the devil for his soul back. In these lines he blames the devil for nearly derailing his career, as he said it was on track until he let the devil lead the way.

Now he HAS his soul, and he’s not letting it go ever again for anything.

“Binky” refers to a pacifier (or dummy in some variations of English), an item given to infants or babies to suck on, intended to stop them from crying. Because they spend so much time in babies' mouths, they often end up dirty (messy) from saliva.



X references “bon appétit,” a French phrase said to someone about to eat, essentially meaning something along the lines of “enjoy your meal.” Much like a binky would go into an infant’s mouth, food goes into the mouth as well.

Feel like I'm damaged

tate_text:
These lines refer to X’s ex, Geneva Ayala, who accused him of assault. We can even see a girl who looks like her in the official music video of the track:



He’s rapped about the pain the accusations caused him in his songs before. On “Fuck Love” he rapped,

I’m nauseous, I’m dyin'
She ripped my heart right out
Can’t find her, someone to—
My eyes are all cried out

and on “Revenge” he questioned,

Is my pain your freedom?
Is all of my pain your freedom?
Enjoy…

ref_text:
Runaway, runaway
 Runaway, runaway
 I'm holdin' on
 Desperately
 Runaway, runaway
 Runaway, runaway
 I'm holdin' on
tate_text:
The hook, at this point, trails the question that Cole posed at the end of Verse 3, wondering if he’d be able to run away from a lucrative deal at the cost of losing his artistic integrity.

In a sense, the word “runaway” that is repeated in the hook at this point refers to actually doing the honorable thing, maintaining J. Cole’s true sense of self and not being bought, whereas during the rest of the song, “running away” was associated with less principled behavior, like indulging in his unrestrained desires at the cost of cheating on his faithful woman.

This could be interpreted as him, by the end of the song, finally learning to own up to doing the noble thing
or…
it could be interpreted as him still being selfish and not compromising his self-serving behavior, even for the possibility of making 50 million dollars. It could be argued that maintaining one’s own artistic integrity is not necessarily a selfless thing. It is perhaps axiomatically selfish behavior… though that’s an argument for another time.

In all fairness, it’s likely that “running away” at this point simply refers to running away from situations that a person isn’t comfortable dealing with, like Chappelle having to continue a show that wasn’t sending the message he wanted to send or like a black slave having to take care of a child that was made through slaveowner rape. Would he have the power to run away from these situations, knowing that it’s probably practical to stay?

ref_text: Turn up the bass 'til it's up-in-yo-face level
tate_text:
When bass is really loud, you can actually feel it in your chest. But he means to turn it on so much louder that you’ll feel it in your face.

And apart from being physically in your face, the sound will take a direct stab at your dignity, like a bad neighbor turning up the music up to the max, then taunting you with a provocative “In your face”

ref_text:
‘Cause Marshall Mathers, the rapper's persona
 Is half a facade,
tate_text:
Em’s always had a three-part persona: Eminem, Slim Shady and Marshall Mathers.

As time has gone on, Marshall Mathers has become almost like a stage name, i.e it’s fake. His entire life is just a facade, and rapping is his real life. Eminem and Shady have become him, and he’s lost touch with his true identity. The price of fame.

Motherfuckers know that I’ll never be Marshall again
